description: Serves as the AF ISR Agency Certified TEMPEST Technical Authority (CTTA) and TEMPEST Program Manager. Represents the AF ISR Agency as a TEMPEST expert on international, national, joint, DoD, NSA/CSS and tri-service agency panels, committees, working groups and conferences. Provides TEMPEST/EMSEC relevant training. Develops and validates TEMPEST certification and accreditation documentation in accordance with NSA, DIA and AF guidance.

title: Fellow - DoD Executive Leadership Development Program
description: Participants of ELDP graduate from the program with an increased understanding and appreciation for today’s warfighters. Warfighters speak of being at the “tip of the spear" - ELDP provides those experiences. The program was established in 1985 with the approval of the Secretary of Defense and has continued over the years to train the Department’s future leaders to recognize and respond to the issues facing DoD. During the course of the ten months of training, participants will travel to a variety of locations both in the United States and overseas, to train with the warfighter. Through intense, hand-on field experience, participants experience first hand the many challenges that our Components face in carrying out the mission of the Department. ELDP is not for everyone. It is both mentally and physically challenging. It is designed for high potential individuals who have the desire to progress into senior leadership roles in the Department.

title: Chief, Information Assurance Branch
description: Plans, organizes and directs the activities of the Information Assurance (IA) Branch. These IA activities include the areas of TEMPEST, COMSEC, COMPUSEC, Identity Management, IA Training, and Certification and Accreditation for information systems. Also serves as the AIA Certified TEMPEST Technical Authority and TEMPEST Program Manager. Responsible for control and oversight of compromising emanations and TEMPEST security for all AIA facilities. Conducts TEMPEST evaluations and provides engineering assistance/consultations for AIA facilities and systems. Represents AIA as a TEMPEST expert on international, national, joint DoD, NSA/CSS and tri-service agency panels, committees, working groups and conferences. Provides TEMPEST/EMSEC relevant training. Develops and validates TEMPEST certification and accreditation documentation in accordance with NSA, DIA and AF guidance. Assists in establishing policy and doctrine for Technical Security, based on knowledge and judgment of the threat. Functions as agency representative on matters involving Technical Security countermeasures applications. Serves as an information assurance technical consultant for air/ground voice, video, and data, fixed and transportable intelligence communications systems/facilities and associated cryptographic equipment. Provides advice and reviews for accuracy certification and accreditation documents such as System Security Authorization Agreements (SSAAs) and System Security Plans (SSPs).

description: Serve as MAJCOM TEMPEST Manager. Develops, implements, and enforces TEMPEST policies and criteria for AIA. title: TEMPEST Advisor
description: Serves as the technical expert and liaison to all US government departments and agencies, contractors, and international customers of the National TEMPEST School. Evaluate and advise on the effectiveness and technical accuracy of course training content, course design and methodology. Evaluates instructor knowledge and conducts instructor training classes. Research, identify, and initiate the acquisition and funding for school laboratory equipment that represents the balance between the leading edge and current fielded equipment. Subject matter expert on all aspects of TEMPEST from policy, countermeasure guidance and application to laboratory and field testing. Represent the school on the national level TEMPEST Advisory Group.

title: Principal Engineer
description: TEMPEST Engineering, R&D, Test Evaluations, Design & Prototyping. Was responsible for research tasks aimed at developing source-suppressed monochrome and color CRT displays and color dot matrix printers. Conducted performance analysis of cryogenic-cooled, thermal infra-red and laser based shearography imaging and detection systems for physical security applications. Designed and constructed a low-power, high-reliability, sensing and interlocking circuit used for advanced security applications (patent pending). Accountable for the design and prototyping of advanced, low-power, RF based surveillance transmitting systems used for government law enforcement. Designed, prototyped, and installed narrow and wideband fiber-optic based telemetry and video communications systems for use within the Tomahawk Cruise Missile during high-level E-field susceptibility testing. Designed and developed prototype, ultrasonic emitting devices used for government technical security applications. Designed and prototyped a battery powered, fiber-optic based internal communication system (ICS) that was tested with Navy F-14, F-18, and C-130 aircraft during EMI susceptibility testing. Performed engineering evaluations of non-metallic, photonic-based, EM sensors when used during E-field measurements of simulated EM pulse (EMP) phenomena. Assisted in developing EMI & RFI solutions for the US Army Black Hawk helicopter. Provided RF engineering analysis for the US Navy to determine antenna interactions on the next generation aircraft carrier. Provided on-base engineering support at the Naval Air Warfare Centers at Patuxant River, Maryland, and Dahlgren, Virginia. Obtained CTP-1 certification.

title: Manager, Product Security Certification
description: Manager, Product Security Certification - Mr. Boland managed the testing and certification of SPYRUS, Inc. products to various security standards including FIPS 140-1, FIPS 140-2, Common Criteria, and ITSEC. Mr. Boland’s efforts at SPYRUS resulted in the successful completion of 7 FIPS 140-1 evaluations (including the first successful FIPS 140-1, Level 3 evaluations of a Smartcard and a USB Token) and 3 algorithm evaluations. Nearing successful completion at the time of his departure from Spyrus were an additional FIPS 140-1 evaluation, an ITSEC (E3) evaluation of the SPYRUS PKI, and a Common Criteria (EAL2) evaluation of a cryptographic Smartcard. Additionally, Mr. Boland devised efficiency methodologies among and across the various certification standards to reduce the cost/time to certification. Other responsibilities included: • Development and management of the Product Security Certification Group, • Development / presentation of training courses focused on designing products to security standards, • Serving on security standards committees and co-editing the financial community’s Protection Profile for Certificate Issuing and Management Systems, and • Providing technical input into the design process of secure communications / key management products and ensuring that security requirements are being met.

title: Sr. Engineer
description: Sr. Engineer, Secure Communications - Mr. Boland served as a senior design engineer for the KG-93/94, STX-34, KUTA MDP, Fabricator, and KGV-10 cryptographic equipments. His responsibilities included digital design, LSI design, TEMPEST design and testing, Cryptographic Verification, Security Fault Analyses, acceptance testing, and training. Additionally, Mr. Boland served as Motorola’s lead resident engineer for the NSA’s Standard Module Program. Mr. Boland led the industry design team for the Standard Key Management Module.

title: Chair, TEMPEST Advisory Group - Committee on National Security Systems
description: The Committee on National Security Systems (CNSS) sets national-level Information Assurance policies, directives, instructions, operational procedures, guidance and advisories for United States Government (USG) departments and agencies for the security of National Security Systems (NSS). It provides a comprehensive forum for strategic planning and operational decision-making to protect NSS and approves the release of INFOSEC products and information to Foreign Governments. Chaired US Working Group setting national policy and standards for the control of compromising emanations. Represented US TEMPEST interests on international standard bodies.

title: Senior Systems Security Engineer
description: IA lead supporting Boeing’s Family of Advanced Beyond line-of-site Terminals (FAB-T) Program. Conducts analysis of engineering solutions and security controls to ensure proper implementation and operation of the level of protection required for the terminal. Recommends valid technical and/or procedural changes to quickly resolve security deficiencies ensuring adherence to program schedule and budget. Creates and flows system engineering requirements that support hardware and software DIACAP IA Controls. Generates all required system DIACAP documentation that fully explains design and processes fulfilling required IA Controls to obtain program IATT, IATO and ATO accreditation decisions. Interfaces with government and industry partners ensuring agreement on IA plans and goals. Supports Defense IA Security Accreditation Working Group (DSAWG) C&A approval process for Cross Domain Solutions used in the FAB-T Architecture. Support NSA Type I Certification activities for embedded uncertified cryptographic units.

title: Senior IA Analyst
description: Provided IA support to the AFSPC IA Division. Conducted in-depth technical reviews of C&A documentation in preparation for Designated Accrediting Authority (DAA) signature. Evaluated systems over the acquisition life cycle and provide guidance on implementation and design of IA security controls. Provided analysis of engineering solutions and security controls to ensure proper implementation and operation of the level of protection required for mission systems. Identified system vulnerabilities and developed risk mitigation. Developed and briefed accreditation recommendations to the DAA Representative (DAAR). Participated in information system risk assessments and Systems Security Working Groups to support program managers in ensuring proper design and testing of security requirements. Reviewed IA security plans, including Continuity of Operations, Incident Response and other supplied documentation to determine the confidentiality, integrity, availability, and non-repudiation capabilities of the associated systems. Planned, coordinated and managed all IA Assessment and Assistance Program (IAAP) Audits of all AFSPC bases and Geographically Separated Units. Assessed all areas of IA to include: Physical Security, Base Network Security, IS Security, C&A, Computer Security (COMPUSEC), Telephone Security (TMAP), Emission Security (EMSEC), COMSEC, Identification and Authentication and malicious logic control. Briefed Commanders on all IAAP findings, created reports and tracked all discrepancies until resolution. Provided DAA and AFSPC subordinate agencies with clarification and interpretation on all Federal, DoD, NSA, DISA, Air Force, and AFSPC guidance pertaining to all aspects of IA and IS protection. Created and implemented the Command’s Wireless Scanning Program and trained all base IA personnel on the program and rules of engagement.

title: Information Assurance
description: Chief, 50th Space Wing (SW) Computer Security, Schriever AFB, Colorado Springs, CO, 2002-2005 Planed, coordinated, and managed 50 SW and Schriever AFB Computer Security (COMPUSEC) programs. Conducted workshops and additional duty training to unit Information Assurance (IA) Awareness managers. Established procedures and provided guidance to ensure all 50 SW Information Systems (IS) were accredited. Represented Wing Commander and Designated Approval Authority (DAA) on computer security issues. Formulated life-cycle security management for computer systems acquisition, development, and testing. Led teams on annual IA Assessments that reviewed computer security for 35 units at 12 worldwide locations. Chief, Maintenance Support, Schriever AFB, Colorado Springs, CO, 2001-2002 Managed maintenance projects, circuit actions, and training related to mission equipment for the Air Force’s $115M Attack and Launch Early Reporting to Theater (ALERT) missile warning system. Managed dual-track maintenance work center training program consisting of formal training and OJT. Maintenance Standardization and Evaluation Program lead—provided maintenance status to commander. Acted in absence of Chief of Maintenance in planning and management of all maintenance functions. Provided hands-on maintenance and technical support to maintenance work center and operations crews. Space, Air, Missile Computer Maintenance Crew Chief, Cheyenne Mountain AS, CO, 1996-2001 Performed preventative and corrective maintenance to ensure continued operation of the $525M Air Defense system, $470M Missile Warning System, and the $467M Space Defense Operations Center (SPADOC) computer systems. Isolated, removed and replaced defective field replaceable units to provide secure, uninterruptible interface processing, data formatting, and display capabilities in support of NORAD, USSPACECOM, and AFSPC.

title: Test Engineer II
description: Responsible for performing high level EMI/EMC/TEMPEST testing on state-of-the-art equipment at the unit and system level to meet NSA, commercial and MIL-STD specification requirements. TEMPEST/EMI/EMC test and design modification experience to include monitors, keyboards, printers, scanners, facsimile and receivers. Mr. Henry is responsible for implementing design modification and performs a variety of tests needed to determine equipment and system level compliance requirements. Modifications include integrated circuit design changes, as well as individual electronic component replacements. Once the modifications are implemented, Mr. Henry uses precision test equipment to test each board-level circuit for compliance to specifications and operation. In his test scenarios, Mr. LoPresti establishes performance baselines and completes the tests using standard test procedures. He documents all modifications and testing results.

title: Manager, Product Security Certification
description: Manager, Product Security Certification - Mr. Boland managed the testing and certification of SPYRUS, Inc. products to various security standards including FIPS 140-1, FIPS 140-2, Common Criteria, and ITSEC. Mr. Boland’s efforts at SPYRUS resulted in the successful completion of 7 FIPS 140-1 evaluations (including the first successful FIPS 140-1, Level 3 evaluations of a Smartcard and a USB Token) and 3 algorithm evaluations. Nearing successful completion at the time of his departure from Spyrus were an additional FIPS 140-1 evaluation, an ITSEC (E3) evaluation of the SPYRUS PKI, and a Common Criteria (EAL2) evaluation of a cryptographic Smartcard. Additionally, Mr. Boland devised efficiency methodologies among and across the various certification standards to reduce the cost/time to certification. Other responsibilities included: • Development and management of the Product Security Certification Group, • Development / presentation of training courses focused on designing products to security standards, • Serving on security standards committees and co-editing the financial community’s Protection Profile for Certificate Issuing and Management Systems, and • Providing technical input into the design process of secure communications / key management products and ensuring that security requirements are being met.

title: Physical Security Specialist
description: Provides oversight and reviews program directives such as the ICD 705 Tech Spec, and DoD 5105.21 to ensure compliance. Reviews Fixed Facility Checklists, self-inspection reports, work requirements, and requests for concept approval for accreditation of Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities (SCIF) and Temporary Secure Working Area (TSWA) authorizations. Reviews documentation to ensure compliance with applicable directives on security alarms and alarm tests, no notice parcel inspections, and security violations. Reviews Emergency Action Plans (EAPs) for supported facilities to provide maximum security based on risk management. Provides guidance and monitors this process for supported SCIFs, maintains master documentation on supported facilities and those under construction; coordinates initial operations and keeps abreast of physical vulnerabilities and policies. Serves as the primary TEMPEST officer for all USTRANSCOM/AMC SCIFs. Ensures compliance with all NSA TEMPEST guidelines and installation criteria. Maintains liaison with the Air Force Office of Special Investigations (AFOSI) on requirements and requests for technical surveys of facilities in which SCI is processed, stored, or discussed. Conducts security assistance visits of support facilities to ensure all physical security requirements are met and recommends corrective action, as required.

title: Consultant / Principal Systems Engineer
description: Requirements definition and analysis, systems integration, and formal verification of software-defined radios for the Joint Tactical Terminal - Integrated Broadcast Service (JTT-IBS) Engineering Test Lead ================= - Created and oversaw execution of system-level test plans and procedures (integration and formal qualification testing) for JTT-IBS system. Formal testing was successful and production units were delivered to the DoD customer. Areas of experience include: - NSA Type 1 Certification - TEMPEST - EMI (MIL-STD-461F) - Environmental (MIL-STD-810F) (Temperature/Altitude/Humidity, Shock, Vibration, Crash Safety, Explosive Atmosphere, Explosive Decompression, Salt Fog, etc) - Software Qualification Testing - Extensive hands-on operation of and trouble-shooting with RF test equipment, tactical communications equipment, UHF satellite simulators, COMSEC keys and devices, in a simulated SATCOM network environment - Provided extensive support to platform integrators for incorporation of JTT-IBS into fixed and mobile platforms. Systems Engineering Lead ===================== - Provided guidance, technical direction, review and signature of contract deliverables. - Addressed requirements gap in the existing performance specification. Revised specification and generated Engineering Change Proposals which were approved by program management and DoD customer. - Collaborated with software engineering to completely revise the existing software requirement specification, consisting of over 1200 requirements, and software test. description and plans for resubmission to certification agency. Certification agency approved the resubmissions - Generated DOORS modules and scripts to facilitate detection of missing and incorrect traces between lower-level and upper-level requirements as well as automate the generation of requirements verification matrices

title: Registered Investment Advisor
description: Mr. Harry W. Gaul is the Managing Director of Tabar Gaul LLC. Mr. Gaul is a Registered Investment Advisor and holds a Series 65 license. He attained his MBA degree from Arizona State University and is a licensed Professional Engineer in the State of Arizona. His 30 years of work in engineering gives him an analytical background that is valuable in assessing the merits of various investment strategies and fund performance. Mr. Gaul decided to become an Investment Advisor as an encore career following a very successful and distinguished career at Motorola and General Dynamics. He saw his own 401k funds languish during several bear markets and he became disenchanted with the way his stockbrokers were all too eager to put him into high fee mutual funds instead of no-load mutual funds and low-fee ETF’s. After this experience, he decided that he could help others avoid the trap of the “standard of suitability” that stockbrokers adhere to. Instead he offers personal services based on the “fiduciary standard” where the advisor manages the client’s funds in the best interests of the client.

title: Physical Security Specialist
description: Provides oversight and reviews program directives such as the ICD 705 Tech Spec, and DoD 5105.21 to ensure compliance. Reviews Fixed Facility Checklists, self-inspection reports, work requirements, and requests for concept approval for accreditation of Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities (SCIF) and Temporary Secure Working Area (TSWA) authorizations. Reviews documentation to ensure compliance with applicable directives on security alarms and alarm tests, no notice parcel inspections, and security violations. Reviews Emergency Action Plans (EAPs) for supported facilities to provide maximum security based on risk management. Provides guidance and monitors this process for supported SCIFs, maintains master documentation on supported facilities and those under construction; coordinates initial operations and keeps abreast of physical vulnerabilities and policies. Serves as the primary TEMPEST officer for all USTRANSCOM/AMC SCIFs. Ensures compliance with all NSA TEMPEST guidelines and installation criteria. Maintains liaison with the Air Force Office of Special Investigations (AFOSI) on requirements and requests for technical surveys of facilities in which SCI is processed, stored, or discussed. Conducts security assistance visits of support facilities to ensure all physical security requirements are met and recommends corrective action, as required.

description: As an entrepreneurial visionary (three patents awarded related to Information Assurance) / problem solver, I am highly skilled at designing and implementing strategic plans to develop, integrate, and/or acquire synergistic technologies and build/manage/mentor multi-functional engineering teams focused on developing and delivering cutting-edge enterprise solutions. title: Assistant Special Security Officer
description: Implemented and executed SCI and collateral sec requirements to include (Army, AF, Marine, Navy, CG) Personnel Security (700+ personnel)), Industrial and Information Sec, SCI Physical Security, Sec Badge and Access Sys and Visitor Control (7000+ U.S. and foreign national visitors yearly) programs, and the Security Awareness, Education and Training and Security Inspections and Self Inspection programs. Completed & validated investigations packets (SF 86), conducted interviews, adjudicated & processed adverse information reports & adjudicated to determine eligibility to classified information, conducted security indocs, debriefs, ensured completion of forms to include NDAs, SF 86s, SF 312s.Determined ind’s suitability, trustworthiness or reliability and granted interim secret/TS clearances. Suspended security clearance access, processed CAF letters and assisted customers with response packets and appeals processing & processing for Personnel Security Adjudication Boards, with DoD CAF. Assist customers with completion of SF 86 and submit to the OPM via JPAS, e-QIP or AIES and monitor investigation status; monitor PR program. Processed requirements for 8 Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities (SCIFs) & secure areas & conducted self-inspections and prepared reports IAW DCID 6/9 (ICD 705) checklist. Prepared SCIF accreditation docs and submitted to DIA and NSA. Supervised construction/renovation projects for 13 newly/renovated SCIFs ensuring DIA & NSA security requirements were met. Processed requirements, performed inspections, and endures sec adherence. Prepared/submitted TEMPEST and PDS documents & maintained DIA TEMPEST accreditation. Processed courier, DEFCOS, packaging and safeguarding SCI. Conducted sec visits, monthly alarm checks & inspections and accredited secure open & closed areas. Administered SAP programs & billets. Administered 21 classified contracts, prepared DD 254s, reviewed contracts & appointed Contract Monitors for SCI contracts.

title: Security Manager
description: Personnel, Physical, & Information security support to Navy afloat ships, shore & Joint Commands. Responsible for security program management, administered, implemented & executed Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) Security & collateral sec requirements to include (Army, AF, Marine, Navy, CG, Civilian, & Contractor) Personnel Security, Information Sec, SCI Physical Security. Processed personnel security actions to include: completed & validated investigations packets (SF 86), conducted interviews, adjudicated and processed adverse information reports & adjudicated to determine eligibility to classified information, conducted security indocs, debriefs, ensured completion of forms to include NDAs, SF 86s, SF 312s, etc. Suspended security clearance access, processed Central Adjudication Facilities letters & assisted customers with response packets & appeals processing and processing for Personnel Security Adjudication Boards, with all military service adjudication facilities. Submit adverse information via JPAS to CAF. Issue CAF Letters of Intent, initiate actions for security clearance suspensions, and assist with LOI responses and appeals processing. Prepared SCIF accreditation docs to include concept plans, FFCs, TEMPEST addendum checklists, Inspect able Space Determination, Co-Utilizations, & submitted to SSO Navy & NSA. Deactivated shipboard SCIFs. Processed requirements, performed inspections, & endured sec adherence. Conducted security inquiries & investigations of security violations & prepared & submitted reports. Implemented comprehensive tracking procedures that resulted in a 99 percent accuracy rate & was cited as the best data call program within NSA. Developed & managed effective security information training programs on both afloat & shore stations in support of over 3,500 DoD military and civilian personnel. Proficient with CONFIRM identification badge control & CONCERTO.

description: Electrical Design Integrated Product Team Lead on an Armored Recovery Vehicle Managed 8 eight engineers and draftsmen from concept through the release of the final drawing package. Expanded project scope by providing hands-on technical assistance to customer in the development of life saving rescue techniques utilizing hydraulic and electric rescue tools on armored vehicles.

title: Sr.Signal Integrity & Electrical Test Engineer
description: Created automated test systems for use in production environments which resulted in 80% man-hour savings to the company. Conducted product qualification testing and root cause of failure analysis on interconnect systems and assemblies. Represented company at EIA / TIA and IEEE standards meetings and work groups by developing test procedures to be industry standard specifications for FiberChannel and SFF-HSSDC. • Saved company $250,000 by developing test apparatus and procedures for the fiber channel wiring harness evaluation and acceptance criteria on the Apache LongBow Helicopter Program. Responsible for selection and purchase of test equipment within $500k budget for use in the test lab. Testing included: Characteristic Impedance, Crosstalk, Propagation Delay, Skew, Rise Time Degradation, Insertion Loss, Return Loss, Bandwidth, Eye Pattern and Jitter measurements. Experienced in usage of digital oscilloscopes, pattern generators, signal generators, time domain Reflectometers, Two port and Four port network analyzers, spectrum analyzers, Member of HSSDC (fibre channel) standard testing work group, USB 1.1 and 2.0 test procedure development

title: Marketing Director
description: When becoming the Marketing Director for the Hughes spinoff Palomar Products, the company was faltering with a shrinking annual revenue down to eight million. It shortly became a vibrant, growing company doing between 25 and 30 million per year, in a small niche market of TEMPEST qualified military airborne secure ICS systems. The primary customers have been Boeing, Lockheed Martin, L-3 Com, Sikorsky and the US Government. For many years, tasks included doing all the trade show coordination, all the marketing, writing all the proposals, generating all the engineering estimates and of course the normal bookings forecasts and strategic business planning. Over the years Palomar added more people to the business development staff, so my main responsibilities recently have been customer contact, helping our customers develop system architecture concepts, writing whitepapers and proposal technical volumes, exhibiting at trade shows, managing the Palomar website, managing many of the proposal efforts and, of course the normal business forecasting and strategic business planning. The last day at this position was April 30th. The consulting business officially started on May 1, 2014

title: Analyst
description: Prepares all-source intelligence products to support the combat commander. Assists in establishing and maintaining systematic, cross-referenced intelligence records and files. Receives and processes incoming reports and messages. Assists in determining significance and reliability of incoming information. Assists in integrating incoming information with current intelligence holdings and prepares and maintains the situation map. Assists in the analysis and evaluation of intelligence holdings to determine changes in enemy capabilities, vulnerabilities, and probable courses of action. Assists in the preparation of Order of Battle records using information from all sources and in the preparation of strength estimates of enemy units. Assembles and proofreads intelligence reports and assists in consolidating them into military intelligence. Prepares Intelligence Preparation of the Battlefield (IPB) products. Analyzes current intelligence holdings to identify gaps, and subsequent intelligence collection requirements. Considers enemy Order of Battle records in the development of collection tasks and assessment of enemy vulnerabilities and probable courses of action. Assists in the preparation of reports on captured enemy material. Drafts periodic and special intelligence reports, plans, and briefings.

title: Special Security Representative
description: Responsible for all aspects of personnel & information security, to include: physical, personnel, information, & technical security. Duties involve the management, supervision, or performance of work in developing, evaluating, maintaining, & operating systems, policies, devices, procedures & methods used for safeguarding classified SCI information, property, & materials. Supervises the operation of the Special Security Office & administering the SCI security program to include SCI security oversight. Supervises the construction Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility (SCIF) to include accreditation, upgrades, & introduction of new equipment. Passes SCI access certifications. Conducts & manages SCI personnel, information, physical, & technical security (TEMPEST/ TSCM) actions & procedures according to DOD, NSA, CIA, regulations. Conducts SCI security briefings, indoctrinations, & debriefings; obtains signed Nondisclosure Agreements; & performs related personnel security actions. Conducts a continuing SCI security education training & awareness program to ensure that SCI indoctrinated individuals are kept apprised of requirements & guidelines for protecting SCI. Ensures appropriate accreditation documentation is available for each SCIF & communications/automated information systems under the organization's security cognizance. Reviews derogatory information from local supporting military law enforcement agency involving SCI-indoctrinated personnel & takes appropriate action. Maintains continuing liaison with non-SCI security officials. Produces, reviews, & manages emergency plans for the SCIF. Constantly evaluate SCI risk & recommend appropriate countermeasures. Creates Standard Operating Procedures (SOPS) for operations involving use or transport of classified material. Investigates or assists in the investigation of security violations & Practices Dangerous to Security (PDS) & advise the Task Force ACE Chief, DG2, & G2 on investigations IAW DoD 5105.21-M-1.

title: Detailed Officer
description: OVERVIEW: Serve as a primary senior advisor and special assistant to the Deputy Assistant Secretary for Security at the Department of the Treasury. Ensure Treasury Security program’s compliance with national standards, CNSS requirements, and IC Community guidelines. Support tactical requirements/services in TSCM and TEMPEST areas. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Provide fact-based reporting to senior issues and executive-level guidance/recommendations. Serve as a key facilitator in engaging support staff and addressing/resolving mission-critical risk matters. ★ Leverage 20+ years of security expertise and leadership to infuse a young organization with the tools/strategies necessary for building a strong program and long-term success. ★ Currently serve as the Co-Chair of the CNSS NTSWG National Telephone Security Working group.

title: Chief of Special Security Programs Divisions
description: OVERVIEW: Directed 11 branches in providing facility security coverage to all DHS facilities within the Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) security program areas, as well as coverage to DHS’ HQ (SCI and operational security support services). Oversaw DHS accreditation for over 150,000 sq. ft. of classified work space spanning 100+ facilities nationwide, ensuring compliance with national standards (services covered federal, state, and local govt.). Led and conducted investigations of security incidents; directly involved in all DHS HQ reported security volition/incidents. Worked with Office Director of National Intelligence (ODNI) as a subject matter expert to support new accreditations/policies in support of ICD 705. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Grew the Division to 11 branches with a mix of 60+ federal staff and contractors who supported the daily operations of DHS’ SCI programs. ★ Maintained services and staffing during rapid growth period of HQ and DHS facilities, ensuring presence of functional security support teams. ★ Developed operational policies and guidelines that enabled growth and development for future leaders within OSCO HQ; sustained SCI security policy program for DHS.

title: Branch Chief, DHS Facility Accreditation
description: OVERVIEW: Promoted based on expertise and capabilities as a SCI Security Intel Officer. In charge of developing and executing accreditation program for DHS Sensitive Classified Information (SCI) programs. Additionally led interface between DHS, other govt. organizations and industry contractors in developing the SCI facility as a Technical Security Officer and Certified Technical Tempest Authority (CTTA). Reviewed and approved all security plans, working with the federal staff/contractors to ensure successful completion of facility within framework of new accreditation process. Led team of 9 security professionals and coordinated with multiple divisions to ensure consistent implementation of program requirements across DHS. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Involved in the accreditation of over 60 facilities covering ~100,000 sq. ft. of classified facilities space; earned promotion to GS-15 for accomplishments in this position. ★ Ensured appropriate staff / management levels in hiring 100+ employees for critical security positions during rapid growth period within DHS. Brought top talent on board to fulfill the DHS mission. ★ Created policies and Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) to support the SCI mission at DHS, reversing prior history of limited policies/SOPs within the operation. ★ Created IC badging program for DHS that reducing security staff work on passing clearance; developed customer engagement program that reduced facilities costs and services. Facilitated DHS integration with IC Partners through use of the IC Badge.

title: Information Systems Manager
description: OVERVIEW: Held multiple roles and responsibilities. At the National Reconnaissance Officer (NRO), served as the TEMPEST authority in managing all NRO Technical TEMPEST Security programs (covering govt. and contractor facilities) from 1998 to 2004. As Technical Security Officer and Certified Technical TEMPEST Authority, managed interface between govt. organizations and contractors to develop Certified Automated Processing Systems in compliance with DCID 6/3 and NISPOM standards. Reviewed all IT system security plans and worked directly with contractors to ensure successful completion of Intelligence Community accreditation processes. Provided support for Government Industrial Security Program activities. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Served as a Technical Security Subject Matter Expert on several ODNI Intelligence Community technical working groups; acted as the CIA member of the TEMPEST Advisory Group. ★ Led team in developing communication equipment room (CER) standards; policy defined requirements that included physical, environmental, and electrical requirements for construction of CER within a sensitive, compartmented information facility. ★ Directly involved in efforts to revise the NSTISSAM (National Security Telecommunications and Information System Security Policy) as a member of the subcommittee. ★ Worked with representatives from multiple agencies to write DCID 6/9 (Director of Central Intelligence Directive) during numerous reviews to address key changes. Collaborated with individuals from the NSA, CIA, DIA, NRO, and DEO.

title: Manager, Product Security Certification
description: Manager, Product Security Certification - Mr. Boland managed the testing and certification of SPYRUS, Inc. products to various security standards including FIPS 140-1, FIPS 140-2, Common Criteria, and ITSEC. Mr. Boland’s efforts at SPYRUS resulted in the successful completion of 7 FIPS 140-1 evaluations (including the first successful FIPS 140-1, Level 3 evaluations of a Smartcard and a USB Token) and 3 algorithm evaluations. Nearing successful completion at the time of his departure from Spyrus were an additional FIPS 140-1 evaluation, an ITSEC (E3) evaluation of the SPYRUS PKI, and a Common Criteria (EAL2) evaluation of a cryptographic Smartcard. Additionally, Mr. Boland devised efficiency methodologies among and across the various certification standards to reduce the cost/time to certification. Other responsibilities included: • Development and management of the Product Security Certification Group, • Development / presentation of training courses focused on designing products to security standards, • Serving on security standards committees and co-editing the financial community’s Protection Profile for Certificate Issuing and Management Systems, and • Providing technical input into the design process of secure communications / key management products and ensuring that security requirements are being met.

title: Analyst
description: Prepares all-source intelligence products to support the combat commander. Assists in establishing and maintaining systematic, cross-referenced intelligence records and files. Receives and processes incoming reports and messages. Assists in determining significance and reliability of incoming information. Assists in integrating incoming information with current intelligence holdings and prepares and maintains the situation map. Assists in the analysis and evaluation of intelligence holdings to determine changes in enemy capabilities, vulnerabilities, and probable courses of action. Assists in the preparation of Order of Battle records using information from all sources and in the preparation of strength estimates of enemy units. Assembles and proofreads intelligence reports and assists in consolidating them into military intelligence. Prepares Intelligence Preparation of the Battlefield (IPB) products. Analyzes current intelligence holdings to identify gaps, and subsequent intelligence collection requirements. Considers enemy Order of Battle records in the development of collection tasks and assessment of enemy vulnerabilities and probable courses of action. Assists in the preparation of reports on captured enemy material. Drafts periodic and special intelligence reports, plans, and briefings.

title: Special Security Representative
description: Responsible for all aspects of personnel & information security, to include: physical, personnel, information, & technical security. Duties involve the management, supervision, or performance of work in developing, evaluating, maintaining, & operating systems, policies, devices, procedures & methods used for safeguarding classified SCI information, property, & materials. Supervises the operation of the Special Security Office & administering the SCI security program to include SCI security oversight. Supervises the construction Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility (SCIF) to include accreditation, upgrades, & introduction of new equipment. Passes SCI access certifications. Conducts & manages SCI personnel, information, physical, & technical security (TEMPEST/ TSCM) actions & procedures according to DOD, NSA, CIA, regulations. Conducts SCI security briefings, indoctrinations, & debriefings; obtains signed Nondisclosure Agreements; & performs related personnel security actions. Conducts a continuing SCI security education training & awareness program to ensure that SCI indoctrinated individuals are kept apprised of requirements & guidelines for protecting SCI. Ensures appropriate accreditation documentation is available for each SCIF & communications/automated information systems under the organization's security cognizance. Reviews derogatory information from local supporting military law enforcement agency involving SCI-indoctrinated personnel & takes appropriate action. Maintains continuing liaison with non-SCI security officials. Produces, reviews, & manages emergency plans for the SCIF. Constantly evaluate SCI risk & recommend appropriate countermeasures. Creates Standard Operating Procedures (SOPS) for operations involving use or transport of classified material. Investigates or assists in the investigation of security violations & Practices Dangerous to Security (PDS) & advise the Task Force ACE Chief, DG2, & G2 on investigations IAW DoD 5105.21-M-1.

title: Chief of Special Security Programs Divisions
description: OVERVIEW: Directed 11 branches in providing facility security coverage to all DHS facilities within the Sensitive Compartmented Information (SCI) security program areas, as well as coverage to DHS’ HQ (SCI and operational security support services). Oversaw DHS accreditation for over 150,000 sq. ft. of classified work space spanning 100+ facilities nationwide, ensuring compliance with national standards (services covered federal, state, and local govt.). Led and conducted investigations of security incidents; directly involved in all DHS HQ reported security volition/incidents. Worked with Office Director of National Intelligence (ODNI) as a subject matter expert to support new accreditations/policies in support of ICD 705. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Grew the Division to 11 branches with a mix of 60+ federal staff and contractors who supported the daily operations of DHS’ SCI programs. ★ Maintained services and staffing during rapid growth period of HQ and DHS facilities, ensuring presence of functional security support teams. ★ Developed operational policies and guidelines that enabled growth and development for future leaders within OSCO HQ; sustained SCI security policy program for DHS.

title: Branch Chief, DHS Facility Accreditation
description: OVERVIEW: Promoted based on expertise and capabilities as a SCI Security Intel Officer. In charge of developing and executing accreditation program for DHS Sensitive Classified Information (SCI) programs. Additionally led interface between DHS, other govt. organizations and industry contractors in developing the SCI facility as a Technical Security Officer and Certified Technical Tempest Authority (CTTA). Reviewed and approved all security plans, working with the federal staff/contractors to ensure successful completion of facility within framework of new accreditation process. Led team of 9 security professionals and coordinated with multiple divisions to ensure consistent implementation of program requirements across DHS. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Involved in the accreditation of over 60 facilities covering ~100,000 sq. ft. of classified facilities space; earned promotion to GS-15 for accomplishments in this position. ★ Ensured appropriate staff / management levels in hiring 100+ employees for critical security positions during rapid growth period within DHS. Brought top talent on board to fulfill the DHS mission. ★ Created policies and Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) to support the SCI mission at DHS, reversing prior history of limited policies/SOPs within the operation. ★ Created IC badging program for DHS that reducing security staff work on passing clearance; developed customer engagement program that reduced facilities costs and services. Facilitated DHS integration with IC Partners through use of the IC Badge.

title: Information Systems Manager
description: OVERVIEW: Held multiple roles and responsibilities. At the National Reconnaissance Officer (NRO), served as the TEMPEST authority in managing all NRO Technical TEMPEST Security programs (covering govt. and contractor facilities) from 1998 to 2004. As Technical Security Officer and Certified Technical TEMPEST Authority, managed interface between govt. organizations and contractors to develop Certified Automated Processing Systems in compliance with DCID 6/3 and NISPOM standards. Reviewed all IT system security plans and worked directly with contractors to ensure successful completion of Intelligence Community accreditation processes. Provided support for Government Industrial Security Program activities. KEY CONTRIBUTIONS & ACHIEVEMENTS: ★ Served as a Technical Security Subject Matter Expert on several ODNI Intelligence Community technical working groups; acted as the CIA member of the TEMPEST Advisory Group. ★ Led team in developing communication equipment room (CER) standards; policy defined requirements that included physical, environmental, and electrical requirements for construction of CER within a sensitive, compartmented information facility. ★ Directly involved in efforts to revise the NSTISSAM (National Security Telecommunications and Information System Security Policy) as a member of the subcommittee. ★ Worked with representatives from multiple agencies to write DCID 6/9 (Director of Central Intelligence Directive) during numerous reviews to address key changes. Collaborated with individuals from the NSA, CIA, DIA, NRO, and DEO.

title: Sr. Information Assurance Analyst
description: Supporting the Information Assurance (IA) efforts for Fixed Station, Tactical, and Unmanned Aerial Vehicle Certification and Accreditation (C&A) testing efforts. Directly responsible for all contracts, budget and personnel resources that support 14 different Department of Army customers located throughout the United States. Coordinate the C&A test schedule with Prime/Subordinate contractors to complement work associated with the DITSCAP/DIACAP process. Develop the System Security Authorization Agreement (SSAA) Security Requirements Traceability Matrix (SRTM) in conjunction with DOD 5200 and DOD 8500.1/2 requirements. Coordinates the development and updates of system security and accreditation plans and tracking systems, directs management reviews, and make Risk and Vulnerability Assessments, along with providing Security Awareness and Training.

title: Program Manager
description: responsible for managing cryptologic training standards for SIGINT and Morse courses across all services and National Security Agency/Central Security Service. Managed comprehensive training standards for four operational and technical development paths at the basic, intermediate, and advanced levels of Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) analysis and Morse curricula. Coordinated and led multiple SIGINT Cryptologic Training Advisory Groups (CTAG) composed of representative/subject matter experts (SME) from all military services and NSA/CSS, for the purpose of establishing, revising, reviewing, and validating cryptologic training conducted under the auspices of an Executive Agent (EA) or Responsible Training Authority (RTA) to ensure technical adequacy. Managed the daily execution of the Cryptologic Training System (CTS) for SIGINT and Morse programs; encompassed identifying NSA/CSS and joint training requirements, designing and implementing curricula, evaluating training, and ensuring that institutional cryptologic training is accurate, current, and responsive to mission requirements of the field and tactical customers. Databases/Systems used: NSA Net, JWICS, SIPR Net, Intelink, NMCI , AMHS, MS Office (Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Access)

title: Leading Supervisor
description: Led a diverse multi-person team in the Ship’s Signals Exploitation (SSES) in support of operational, national, and Theater commander. Collected Signals intelligence (SIGINT) from various types of intelligence collection assets by utilizing state of the art collection equipment such as Digital Receiver Technology (DRT) equipment and various direction finding (DF) equipment. Analytical work focused on substantive intelligence matters involving Narco-Terrorists groups and various military targets in the Middle East, Horn of Africa, Central, and South America. Driving force behind a highly trained multi-personnel watch floor that resulted in the collection and processing of numerous signals of interest, providing 5th Fleet, Office of Naval Intelligence (ONI), and the National Security Agency/ Central Security Service (NSA/CSS) with critical information. Coordinated efforts in guiding and training personnel in Signals Intelligence collections, Combat Direction Fining (CDF) in support of National and Theater commanders. As Command Personal Qualification Standard (PQS) coordinator; assigned, monitored, and reported on the PQS completion for 240 personnel to ensure that the command maintained qualified personnel to conduct tactical operations in support of National and Theater commanders. Leading Supervisor – Joint Task Force Guantanamo (JTG-GETMO) Guantanamo Bay Cuba; As Sergeant of the Guard (SOG) supervised 89 highly trained maximum security personnel. Responsible for the day-to-day safe and humane treatment of more than 160 Global War on Terrorism detainees within the maximum confines of the maximum security facility Camp Delta. Made amazing contributions to the resounding success of opening the $37 million maximum security detention facility at camp Delta. Charged with the care of 89 highly trained detainee guards in extremely arduous conditions and effectively kept moral high. Responsible for the safe and humane detainment of over 160 enemy combatants.

title: Certified Master Training Specialist
description: Basic Communication Signals collection course instructor; led and managed numerous multi-service students and multiple staff, facilitating graduation of 32 classes with a 96% graduation rate. title: IT Specialist
description: IT specialist with the ‘Dnet’ project supporting the design, develop and deployment of a secure network infrastructure at 50+ domestic sites with Internet, VoIP and IP surveillance for the Drug Enforcement Administration, Office of Investigative Technology (ST). • Design, Development & Deployment phase: Completed six (6) Site Surveys to determine requirements for vBNS circuits/network infrastructure design (large, medium, small site). • Developed a test plan for web proxy, firewall, VPN, IPS solutions at Point of Presence (PoP). • Thoroughly analyzed compliance of network infrastructure with DISA STIGs. Analyzed and evaluated risks associated with the IT systems. • Developed mitigation strategies to implement configuration changes and counter IT vulnerabilities and identified risks. Developed Access Control implementation plan. • Interpret DOJ/DEA policies. Provided technical guidance to organization staff on IT security policies, procedures, and processes. • Achievements: Achieved IATO/ATO prior to the consolidation of the controlled unclassified information (CUI) networks. • Presentations: Moderator for Web 2.0 Summit, CSI Annual Conference (2009); Web Browser Risks presentation

title: Systems Manager/Engineer
description: Systems Manager/Engineer for the ‘IFTS’ project at ISAF HQ (Kabul, Afghanistan) responsible for fielding the NATO Friendly Force Tracking (FFT) capability to NATO’s International Security Assistance Force (ISAF). NATO FFT supports increased situational awareness by providing ground track information to the Common Operational Picture (COP) for NATO coalition force and US forces. (PSA contract). • Completed Interconnection tasks for NATO-Nation Interoperability (NNI) requirement. • Represent the organization at ISAF Joint Operations Center (JOC) meetings. Advise all levels of management involving critical network issues. Prepare daily project status reports for senior authorities. • Deployments: Managed 7-12 member deployment teams, • Coordinated installations of 1000+ FFT kits for soldiers and vehicles with military leadership and effectively communicated. • Attentively tracked ~$2M equipment inventory during deployments. • Completed operator and system architecture training and multi-nation training exercises. Communicated complex technical requirements to non-technical personnel. • Customer service; deployed a Help Desk capability and facilitated customer service for escalated issues. • Deployment Achievements: Improved deployment efficiency (40+ locations, 5 regions). • When possible, coordinated with signal officers to mitigate spectrum conflicts with ‘jamming’ devices/vehicle kits.

title: Certification and Accreditation Analyst
description: Certification and Accreditation Analyst with Department of Homeland Security (DHS), Homeland Secure Data Network (HSDN) project responsible for completing the DIACAP process to achieve IATO and ATO for the classified network. • Interpret DHS policies (4300B). Provided technical guidance to organization staff on IT security policies, procedures, and processes. Communicated complex technical requirements to non-technical personnel. • Completed 5+ site security packages and Security Test & Evaluation (ST&E). Analyzed and evaluated risks with Open Secure Storage in a SCIF. Developed mitigation recommendations to counter vulnerabilities and identified risks and resolve shortfalls in IT system security features and practices. • Completed a thorough CTE (Certification Test Evaluation): Analyzed and evaluated risks with the DMZ and Data Center IT systems (perimeter firewalls, NIDs, perimeter/infrastructure routers, core switches and Windows/Linux operating systems). Developed mitigation recommendations to counter vulnerabilities/identified risks and resolve shortfalls in IT system security features and practices.

title: Certifying Agent
description: As a Certifying Agent with Department of State (DoS), Site and Systems Application Certification Team, the goal was to achieve an ATO for all unclassified/classified major applications and networks supporting the Diplomatic Posts and Bureaus worldwide. • Team Lead for Security Test & Evaluations (ST&E) for unclassified/classified IT systems. • Verified system protective controls and compliance with NIST 800-53; Analyzed and evaluated risks associated with IT systems for 20+ OCONUS sites, 7+ major applications and 1 LAN network (General Support System) for Public Affairs. Developed mitigation recommendations to counter IT vulnerabilities/identified risks and resolve shortfalls in IT system security features and practices. Provided technical guidance to organization staff to harden IT systems. • Interpret DoS policies (FAM/FAR). Provided technical guidance to organization staff on IT security policies, procedures, and processes. • Completed thorough security control evaluations with attention to detail. • Effectively communicated evaluation findings and recommendations for remediation. • Achievements: Team achieved 100% ATO for all OCONUS Diplomatic Posts. Recognized for Site Certification Effort (2004).

title: Network Engineer/Systems Analyst/Internet Security
description: Duties: Webmaster, Network Engineer, Network Security Chief Installed and maintained: A one server 50 client Novell LAN A six server 600 client Windows 2000 server WAN A IBM AS/400 Lotus Domino server Two IBM AS/400 Web Servers Two F5 3DNS DNS servers serving as load balancers Two IBM AS/400 Firewalls running IBM'S firewall Five Phoenix Firewalls Two Cyberguard Firewalls Five Cisco routers Two T-1 lines Duties: Checked the logs of all the perimeter devices for hack attempts daily (firewalls, routers, load balancers and web servers) If one was detected, researched whether a network breach occurred. Performed internal network vulnerability tests prior to contracting to an external accredited security firm. Worked with the internal auditors to prepare for the federal audits. Engineered, built and maintained all the hardware necessary ($1.2mil) for an online banking system. Designed, developed and maintained the main web site. Supervised two employees to help maintain the web site. Accomplishments: Web site was penetration tested by five different companies over the years and none of the companies were able to find a vulnerability that could be exploited. Never had any findings by the local or Federal banking auditors

title: Webmaster, Network Engineer, Network Security Chief
description: Installed and maintained: A one server 50 client Novell LAN A six server 600 client Windows 2000 server WAN A IBM AS/400 Lotus Domino server Two IBM AS/400 Web Servers Two F5 3DNS DNS servers serving as load balancers Two IBM AS/400 Firewalls running IBM'S firewall Five Phoenix Firewalls Two Cyberguard Firewalls Five Cisco routers Two T-1 lines Duties: Checked the logs of all the perimeter devices for hack attempts daily (firewalls, routers, load balancers and web servers) If one was detected, researched whether a network breach occurred. Performed internal network vulnerability tests prior to contracting to an external accredited security firm. Worked with the internal auditors to prepare for the federal audits. Engineered, built and maintained all the hardware necessary ($1.2mil) for an online banking system. Designed, developed and maintained the main web site. Supervised two employees to help maintain the web site. Accomplishments: Web site was penetration tested by five different companies over the years and none of the companies were able to find a vulnerability that could be exploited. Never had any findings by the local or Federal banking auditors

title: Account Executive
description: I am responsible for the strategic marketing, promotion and sales of ARMAG's ARC Vault and other new, advanced product lines. ARMAG Corporation is committed to maintaining leadership in the pre-manufactured SCIF industry. A vital part of the ARMAG design and manufacturing process is a thorough and ongoing discussion throughout the project with the customer regarding not only structural, environmental, network, and security needs, but also the process and coordination of efforts in order to receive accreditation under ICD 705. It is critical to work with the customer throughout the planning, design, production, transportation, and installation in order to properly address any security issues beyond our current rigorous processes. Examples include pre-fabricated secure modular hardened (individual or complex of) survivable facilities to meet the core needs for a communications/data center, command center, administrative offices, standby generator and emergency operations support center for corporate, government and military customers. ARMAG offers a variety of scalable options for secured classified relocatable modular facilities to your needs and requirements. ARMAG also offers expertise in fulfilling TEMPEST requirements, radio-frequency (RF) shielding and electro-magnetic pulse (EMP) hardening for full spectrum communications and data protection. www.armagarcvault.com

title: Cyber Operations Planner
description: Regional Desk Officer (RDO) USCYBERCOM J54 Office, where I provided planning, policy, requirements, and Cyber integration for multiple Department of Defense (DOD) Combatant Commands (COCOMs) worldwide. Specifically, utilized USAF career and technical Cyber planning experience to identify and develop strategic and operational level Cyber mission opportunities, report on evolving Cyber policy trends and issues; as well as review and evaluate strategic Information Operations (IO) policy directives/documents and measured how those policies integrate and affect operational Cyber mission plans. This resulted in superior support to HQ USCYBERCOMMAND J54 Partnership Division. As USPACOM Area of Responsibility Regional Desk Officer (RDO), provided planning, policy, requirements, and integration support for foreign partners in the USPACOM AOR to USCYBERCOM. Responsible for identifying and developing mission enhancement opportunities, reporting on evolving Cyber policy trends and issues; review and evaluate IO policy directives/documents. Conducted research that focused on rapidly emerging cyber warfare threats, and the methods and processes employed by adversary cyber warfare techniques in operations, as well as offensive capabilities; provided support to enhance Cyber requirements analysis and tracking process, including highly focused studies and analyses to support development of processes for the identification, refinement, and prioritization methodology of Cyber requirements.

description: Presently hold Secret clearance. title: Deputy Chief, Technical Security
description: Responsible for the development of written policy pertaining to protection of national security related information and other sensitive information in electronic form from interpretation and exploitation. Promulgates Army COMSEC and ISSM policy, which provides security policy and doctrine for the protection of Army resources and the identification, deterrence and prevention of worldwide threats. Actions result in the safeguarding of national security and national security related information. Plans, analyzes, implements, and evaluates policies and procedures for identifying and protecting COMSEC, Key Management Infrastructure (KMI) and Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) material and equipment from national threats. Recommends the development and prepares COMSEC, TEMPEST and ISSM plans, programs, policies, and doctrine. Interprets Executive Orders, National Security Directives, DoD Policy and Instructions. Orchestrates the planning schedules and conducts Staff Assistance Visits on all Army commands to remain compliant with NSA guidelines. Serves as the Army representative on various Service, DoD, and National level committees and working groups. Extensive knowledge of AR 380-5, AR 380-27, AR 380-40, AR 380-53, AR 50-5, TB 380-40 and TB 380-41, which relate to procedures involving accurate safeguarding and handling of COMSEC material, Communications Security Monitoring and TEMPEST matters.

title: Communications Security Account (Alternate Account Manager)
company: Administrative Assistant to the Secretary of the Army
description: Responsible for management, accountability, receipt, control, transfer, shipment and final destruction of COMSEC material. Delegating authority and overseeing overall planning and coordination of daily operations of HQDA COMSEC program. Wrote correspondence relating to accomplishment of duties, reporting incidence and situations requiring additional investigation and other similar actions. Developed and coordinated plans and programs, which govern management of COMSEC assets. Provided technical guidance to users and the techniques for application of both hardware and software systems. Certified in both areas; the Local COMSEC Management Software (LCMS) and Standardized COMSEC Custodian Course (SCCC). Expert knowledge of COMSEC Key Processor (KP), LCMS workstation and STE phones, which collectively form the service users software known as Electronic Key Management System (EKMS). Remains current with security guidelines, regulations and directives from all governmental levels and provided management input when recommended policy changes were needed. Assists various HQDA staff agencies in preparing COMSEC facility accreditation packages, reaccreditations, and withdrawals of accreditation, emergency action plans, and standard operating procedures in support of accounts located in the National Capital Region. Orchestrates the planning schedules and serves as the lead for all semiannual inspections and annual Staff Assistance Visits of COMSEC facilities to maintain compliance with NSA guidelines. Conducts preliminary investigation of security incidents and violations; assessed damage and develops methods to prevent reoccurrence. Prepared reports of findings and notified NSA and CSLA accordingly. Developed, wrote and implemented the Emergency Action Plan, HQDA COMSEC Hand Receipt Holders Guide and the Personnel Reliability Program for the HQDA COMSEC office.

title: Software Developer
description: Designed and developed two cloud-based software applications. Tempest-GEMS is a grant expense management system that assist municipal, county, and state governments through the financial recovery process after a natural disaster. Tempest-GEMS organizes and tracks financial information and evidentiary documents as required by US federal granting agencies such as FEMA and HUD. Tempest-Time responds to the very complex nature of billing time while working in the disaster recovery workspace. FEMA requires very specific tracking information for direct, and indirect activities. Additionally, FEMA requires that time be track to individual projects within grant programs and disasters. Tempest-time address the required complexity with a friendly and simple interface. Both products have been developed in Oracle and offered through redundant and secure hosting. www.StormPetrel.us for more information.

title: Software Engineer
description: The following efforts pertain to TACLANE HAIPE (High Assurance IP Encryptor) products: DIAGNOSTICS: * Architected and fielded General Dynamic (GD) “Manufacturing Test Controller” (MTC), facilitating the first mass-production of GD encryptors (TACLANE-Micro/KG-175D). A vital team member of the automation and Group Lead of MTC development. The success of MTC was also leveraged for future GD HAIPE products. * Developed Perl scripts to verify bit streams during environmental (EMI/TEMPEST) diagnostics. EMBEDDED: * Designed and developed applications managing encryption keys within the TACLANE architecture. * Designed and developed the Topology service [HAIPE-NETWORKING-MIB] which maintains local and remote IPv4/IPv6 routes. Supports routing protocols, SNMP requests and populates the fast-path. * Designed and developed Runtime applications such as the Inter-Process Communication (IPC), Event Filtering, Alarm Handling, and the Notification Log. * Executed Systems Engineering test plans for: Internet Group Management Protocol (IGMP), Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP), and Multicast Listener Discovery (MLD). Protocol traffic analyzed via WireShark. TOOLS: * Produced and presented to NSA the “GD TACLANE Development Platform” with on-site training. * Developed the “TACLANE Metalinker”, a build utility which formats hardware and software images from an XML specification. Supports boot-loaders, NSA signing, field software upgrades and lab testing. * Implemented the MONGOOSE encryption and its data transport for a SCIP signaling simulation tool. * Developed a C code generator in Perl for specifying TACLANE’s IPSec Security Policy Database (SPD).

title: Sr. Program Security Specialist
description: Provides industrial, personnel, and physical security, specializing in SCIF construction surveillance, inspection, accreditation and certification, including STC and TEMPEST requirements. Imparts guidance for security programs to safeguard classified information, mitigates security vulnerabilities, and conducts inquiries of security violations. Implementation of pertinent personnel security policies contained in Executive Orders (E.O. 12968), (DoD 5200.2-R), SCI (DCID 6/9, ICDs and the ICPG/ICD 705.2/705.3 series) as well as the NISPOM/supplements requirements and SAP. Classified materials handling, receipt, transmittal, destruction, incorporations audits, classified faxes, reproduction, top secret verses secret protection, etc. Monitors and documents security training. Investigates PENREN security breaches and incidents. Processes background checks and ascertains suitability of all employees, contractor workforce and visitors. Makes security determinations for access to national security information. Controls SIPR/NIPRNET access requests and logs via JPAS, JWICS, SIMS networks and databases. Processes photo permit applications, contractor visit clearances utilizing personnel security, adjudicative, and investigative guidelines and directives. Weekly interaction with NSA, DIA, OSD, AOSD, Army, USACE, USN (SECNAV), USAF, AFIAA, USMC, JAFAN, and CENTCOM, and AFRICOM officials providing SCI accreditation.

title: Construction Surveillance Technician
description: Conducted ongoing anti-terror and threat assessments, as well as oversaw on-going tactical and physical security, while monitoring New Consulate Compound (NCC), SAA grounds, CAA, and Access Control Facility (ACF). Provided container de-cert, training, developed emergency translation flyers for LGF, and ensuring proper operation of the full spectrum of technical surveillance equipment to identify anomalies, IEDs, WMDs. Routinely responded to intrusion detection alarms, as well as local Intel alerts from the local guard force concerning eminent Taliban attacks, multiple local explosions and random small arms fire. Constantly monitored foreign national workforce and armed local guard force, as well as domestic contractors’ activities to identify threats and discover surveillance device implantation. Revised and amended the security schematics identifying zone alarm locations in relation to the corresponding cameras and varied guard recon schedules.

title: Site Security Manager & Safety Manager
description: Management of all aspects of Physical Security, Information Security, Personnel Security for the NEC and NOX project. Processed all NCIC and NACLC background checks via the JPAS and conducted all indoctrination, and scheduling for domestic contractors and foreign national workforce. Analyzed and evaluated multi-source intelligence/security investigative data to determine the potential for terrorism, subversion, sabotage or espionage with our Foreign National Security Investigator analyzing, researching, reviewing and interpreting threats. Managed the reinvestigation, and security management cable reporting via JWICS informational exchange. Managed all SCI project areas, screening checkpoints, and surveillance equipment. Utilized NCIC and JPAS for verification of clearances and site access. Performed indoctrinations, annual re-indoctrinations and debriefs. Reviewing and routing foreign travel documents. Oversaw access control and personnel security, building access key control and badge issuance. Supervised surveillance equipment and ensured perimeter security. Monitored sally port’s vehicle inspection area and its armed foreign national security force, including the performance and training of the Local Guard Force (LGF). Managed the embassy’s Cleared Access Areas (CAA), including all security-related equipment at the project site. Conducted Threat Analysis and Threat Surveillance Countermeasures (TSCM) and the daily team-led overall threat assessments with the Surveillance Detection Team using the latest X-ray interpretation equipment to identify explosives, IEDs, and other weapons of mass destruction.

title: ESH Manager & Alternate Antiterrorism Officer
description: BOSC Contract Safety Management of all NGA, CMSI, and subcontracted work activities. Responsible for the development of the first effective Disaster Prep Plan (DPP), Emergency Evacuation Plan (EEP) and Incident Command (IC). Participated in On-Scene Commander activities and reporting, as well as the related WMD exercises, operational information and procedures, and the development and updates to the agency’s various security and safety operational plans. Active Member in Anti-Terrorism Office’s - Threat Working Group, and participated in Security Breach (Red Weapon) exercises. Consultant to ATO for explosive and gas testing monitoring equipment, handling discoveries of Volatile Organic Compounds, suspicious powders, possible anomalies. Managed WMD, CBRNE, and Chem-Decon training for agency’s mail handling center. Oversaw chemical and HAZMAT testing, abatement, transport and disposal. Ensured project compliance with all applicable CFR’s, building codes and security regulatory agencies. Specialized in Site-Security, Site Plan Review (design & implementation) Perimeter Surveillance equipment, Delta barriers, and Pipe Bollard systems, and Electronic Access Control, Stand-off protection (explosion barriers, reinforced perimeter wall design) and blast-proof coating materials. Disaster Preparation Development and Emergency Evacuation Procedures, Chemical Decon Station (Design, Implementation and Operation) and Fire suppression Systems.

title: EMC Test Engineer.
description: - Electromagnetic compatibility testing for product certification to worldwide regulatory standards. Set-up test conditions, conduct tests, document test results and communicate results for any and all EMC tests. - FCC 47/CFR Part 15 using ANSI C63.4 test methods - CISPR 22/EN55022 conduced and radiated emissions (semi-anechoic chamber and 10 meter OATS). - CISPR 24/EN55024 immunity, including IEC/EN 61000-4-2, 4-3, 4-4, 4-5, 4-6, 4-8, 4-11, 3-2, 3-3, 3-11, 3-12. - VCCI (Japan), BSMI (Taiwan), C-Tick (Australia/New Zealand) - Certification testing on Teradata platforms. - Engineering tests on Teradata platforms, and rack enclosure. - Rack magnetization testing (IATA air shipment regulations) - Experience operating Rohde & Schwarz ESU and ESMI receivers using EMC32 software for control. - Testing and calibrations (cable and attenuator) performed in accordance with an ISO 17025 quality system. - Normalized site attenuation (NSA) measurement during certification process.

title: Senior Project Engineer
description: Designed and developed signal distribution/collection/analysis systems including both hardware and software components. Interpreted customer specifications and developed appropriate system solutions. Provided customers with design reviews and technical progress reports. Provided documentation to include hardware and software manuals, test procedures, and reliability analysis. Coordinated company assets to move projects from conception through delivery. Developed audio, digital, and video buffers and switches, AC and DC power monitors, audio and RF programmable amplifiers, VOX circuits, and redundant power supplies. Designed microprocessor circuits to control switches and receivers under extreme altitude and temperature conditions. Extensive experience with CAD-based design including circuit and thermal analysis, modeling, schematic capture, and multi-layer PCB layout. Evaluated PC-based design tools such as circuit simulators, processor emulators, cross-compilers, and various CAD packages. Developed 3-level switch simulation software in C to determine optimum hardware design for large multi-rack signal distribution systems. Designed BEESTING receiver software in C and assembler on a PC platform for an 8051 target. Managed and directed three programmers developing real-time 3-level switching software running on redundant computers for the NEWSPAPER video switch. Design Engineer for the CAMSLANT Coast Guard operator console system. Project Engineer for the MIGRATION avionics audio/digital switch and NEWSPAPER 3-level video switch. title: Security Manager
company: Officer of Inspector General United States Postal Service
description: Office of Inspector General, USPS 1/2012 – Present Grade Level: GS-14 Security Manager. 0080, GS-14 Manage and direct Physical Security, Personnel Security, Emergency Management and Security Education and Training for the Office of Inspector General, United States Postal Service. This includes the OIG Headquarters building located in Arlington, Virginia and 107 field offices located throughout the United States. Developed and implemented a Continuity of Operations Plan for Headquarters, procured and implemented an OIG Emergency Notification System, streamlined the personnel security background investigation process transitioning from paper to electronic, initiated a nationwide field office Keyless Initiative Program and standardized access control and alarm installation processes. Developed a comprehensive Headquarters vulnerability assessment that is used as a template for field offices throughout the country. I also developed and personally provided on site security training to 5 presidentially appointed Postal Regulatory Commissioners (PRC) and the entire PRC staff. I also developed a workplace violence presentation that was featured in LRP Publications and briefed at the annual Federal Workplace Conference at National Harbor in April 2013. I act as the Deputy Director and Director of Logistics and Mission Support upon request. I am also responsible for ensuring all OIG Field Office Federal Law Enforcement Officers and Auditors meet the OIG’s expectations regarding access control, Law Enforcement Sensitive Information storage and handling, weapons and ammunition storage, and the overall compliance with documented security protocol. I work closely with the Safety Officer and assist in Field Office Inspections, safety procedures and asbestos identification in Postal Inspection look out galleries. I hold a TS security clearance based on a current SSBI and I am SCI eligible.
