title: Special Security Officer
description: Manage and direct the SSO operations for the J2 Senior Intelligence Officer, Director of Intelligence and Security, in support of Joint Interagency Task Force South (JIATFS). Manage an effective SCI physical security program supporting six (6) Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities. Set policy and procedures for the command security badge program. Manage and present SCI security awareness and education programs to meet Army and national SCI security requirements. Instruct Security Education and Training at this Joint Task Force to Senior Federal Law Enforcement Officers, Government Civilians, Military Personnel and Government Contractors. This course of instruction is given weekly and includes Operations Security, Information Security, Physical Security, Foreign Disclosure, Special Security and Counter-Intelligence. I am responsible for determining eligibility for interim secret security clearances eligibility based on a variety of factors. I personally handle all letters of intent to suspend security clearances for a multitude of disqualifying factors. Work with CI, NCIS and the FBI when criminal investigations are necessary. Manage JPAS, Scattered Castles and the Full Service Directory accounts for all command personnel. Provide command input to U.S. Southern Command for Quarterly Classification Management Program. As the Terminal Area Security Officer for the Security Directorate I work closely with Information Assurance on procedures for both unclassified and classified computer networks. As the Alternate TEMPEST Control Officer I am responsible for TEMPEST countermeasures to include RF shielded enclosures, ensuring all equipment meets TEMPEST standards. When acting as the Command Security Manager in his absence I work closely with, evaluate and supervise, the Chiefs of Information Assurance, Foreign Disclosure, Counter intelligence and Physical Security.

title: Physical Security Officer
description: Responsible for the execution of the Command's Physical Security Program, Anti-Terrorism/Force Protection and Loss Prevention. This program protects JIATF South staff, visitors, equipment, facilities and information. Agencies on site include all military services, DoD Civilians, Customs, Homeland Security, FBI, DEA, DIA and Foreign Liaison Officers from 11 countries. I am responsible for inspection of facilities, vulnerability assessments, threat assessments, safeguarding personnel, operations and all sensitive material. I work closely with local law enforcement for high profile visits that require personal security details, police escorts or any additional security measures. I continually monitor existing security practices, recommend improvements and take corrective action. I perform security investigations, conduct interviews, prepare and submit reports. I work closely with Counter-Intelligence (CI), Information Assurance (IA) and the Special Security Officer (SSO). I provide security training through face to face classroom instruction from up to date DoD and personally developed curriculum. to over 1,000 military, government and contractors annually. My staff is responsible for the installation, preventive maintenance, replacement and testing of all access control card readers and related work stations and file servers, CCTV, digital recording, bar code scanners, barricades, gate arms, intercoms, turnstiles, bio readers, duress alarms, EST fire alarm, fence alarm, scanners, metal detectors, security containers and NSA government approved shredders. I am the author of the Command Physical Security Plan and Security Officer Standard Operating Procedures Manual. I provide annual Bomb/X-Ray Screening and Suspicious Package Training to security. I work closely with the Safety Officer conducting fire/bomb evacuation drills on a regular basis. I am the lead for the Hurricane Stay Behind Team.

title: Sr. Hardware Engineer
description: Designed Intel StrongARM and PXA based embedded systems including User interfaces, LCD displays and controls. Led a team of multi-disciplined engineers and technicians through a successful deployment of 1500 Phraselators during the Gulf War (in Iraq, Kuwait and Afghanistan). This project started in the back of a napkin, during a meeting with the client that had a problem he wanted to solve, through quick turn prototypes, large production and deployment in theater, all in 135 days. Led the design and development of several products (Bitsy, BitsyX, AGX, VGX) and other custom products for several clients. Led the development and client support on Point of Service equipment (ATM) that was successfully deployed across ATM sites in the US. Interviewed candidates for positions in the company’s engineering teams, with emphasis on their hardware and software development skills.

title: Federal Sales Manager
description: Thinklogical is recognized as the world leader in the design, manufacturing and delivery of fiber-based Routers and Extenders. Thinklogical’s fiber-optic router and extender solutions help organizations control the Sources, Use and Display of KVM, Video and Audio content. For more than a decade, Thinklogical has been a pioneer in the research and development of fiber-optic router solutions, catering to industries that rely on the fast and secure transfer of A/V content each day. Our solutions perform to the highest standards of security, throughput and reliability. Our routers, which have the highest bandwidth in the industry, can be found within the most complex and sensitive government and commercial installations in the world. Thinklogical’s extenders bring real-time KVM capability over distances up to 40 km, enabling organizations to collaborate and share control of assets in ways that were not previously possible. This has in turn generated new workflow methodologies among individuals and groups, allowing for greater productivity and efficiency. Thinklogical is the only supplier that has established an Information Assurance (IA) methodology across high-end video switching equipment accredited by the NSA for Common Criteria EAL4 certification requirements.

title: Army Watercraft C4ISR System Analyst
description: Provides direct government programmatic contractor support, for management and oversight of Army Watercraft Systems (AWS) Sustainment Contract for Command, Control, Communications, Computers, Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (C4ISR). Provides Subject Matter Expertise (SME) for reviewing incident reported failures, on behalf of the Government, insuring that effective scheduling, logistical requirements, and sub-contracting are coordinated to provide most cost effective support In Accordance With (IAW) Performance Work Statement (PWS). Provide technical and analytical support for Failure Analysis, Trend Analysis and Root Cause Analysis of AWS C4ISR Systems. As a System analyst I have applied the current data and programmatic resources documentation to support conclusive and inconclusive theories for the evaluated Failures. This information is utilized to identify and report Product Quality Deficiencies for review. Conduct bi-annual Preventative Maintenance Checks and Services (PMCS) for C4ISR Assets on AWS Vessels located in Kuwait. This PMCS service enabled the AWS, Care Of Supplies in Storage (COSIS), to be groomed for deficiencies and supported the mission readiness of those supporting assets. Provided technical guidance and recommendations for C4ISR system Configuration Management (CM), Product Quality Deficiency Reports (PQDR), Engineering Change Packages (ECP), and Departure from Specifications (DFS) documentation as directed. Provided SME support for the development of AWS C4ISR Technical Manuals (TM) and Technical Bulletins (TB) and assisted in the verification and validation process for Quality Assurance (QA).

title: Field Service Representative
description: Provides management and oversight of Army Watercraft Systems (AWS) Command, Control, Communications, Computers, Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (C4ISR) incident reported failures, and insures that all programmatic resources are utilized to expedite the resolution and recovery of the failed systems. Insures the management of manpower resources, scheduling, logistical requirements, and sub-contracting activities are coordinated to provide effective service and support to the customer. Create technical weekly support documentation and status reports for AWS system failures to support situational awareness of critical and non-critical deficiencies for C4ISR assets. Demonstrate the ability to provide subject matter expertise, and technical service support to identifying, isolating, analyzing and resolving critical C4ISR failures reported by AWS customers within contract guidelines and parameters. Provided technical guidance and field service support for C4ISR equipment to include, system configuration management, wiring and integration of components, and verification of power and data architecture. Provided hands on support during the development of AWS C4ISR Technical Manuals and assisted in the verification and validation process for quality assurance. Effectively apply company methodology and enforces employee guidelines.

title: C4ISR Communications Systems Engineer/Facility Security Officer (FSO)
description: Provided programmatic support to increase current vessel capabilities to meet mission requirements with state-of-the-art commercial legacy and military standardized Tactical Communications equipment. Provided equipment compatibility documentation to the Project Manager Force Projection Enabling Systems, PM Army Watercraft Systems, and U.S. Army Future Watercraft Systems Acquisition Manager (SAM) of C4ISR/CEN equipment supportable within the current fleet logistical system and/or government furnished equipment. Provided technical integration and installation services of equipment to include; wiring of components, termination of connectors and components, and verification of power and data compatibility and capabilities. Conducted Pre and Post instillation equipment verifications, quality control tests, and evaluations for U.S Army Logistic Support Vessel (LSV). Participated in Electronic Magnetic Impulse (EMI) verification and testing on U.S Army Logistic Support Vessel (LSV). Provided technical guidance for the implementation of System Operational Verification Testing (SOVT) procedures for various U.S. Army Watercraft Vessels. Provided Installation Guidance to meet C4ISR/CEN Electromagnetic Interface (EMI) and TEMPEST requirements on the U.S. Army Theater Support Vessel 1X (TSV-1X) to INCAT Shipbuilders in Hobart Australia during developmental phase of Tactical Control Room (TCR). Provide continual life cycle support to the Current Fleet Systems Acquisition Manager (SAM), U.S. Army Tank-Automotive & Armaments Command (TACOM) of periodic assessments to the C4ISR/CEN equipment that enable U.S. Army Watercraft to perform Joint Service Operations within a theater of operations.

title: C4ISR Systems and Training Analyst
description: Provided hands on New Equipment Training (NET) to U.S. Army personnel in support of legacy and Tactical communications equipment upgrades on the Logistic Support Vessel in various locations worldwide. Assisted in the development of training courses material, Technical Publications, and Technical Manuals (TM) for the U.S Army Logistic Support Vessel (LSV) in accordance with Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC) regulations. Evaluated initial installation of the communications equipment for the Systems Acquisition Manager (SAM) of the C4ISR architecture onboard U.S Army A1 and A2 Watercraft and made recommendations for modifications that would enhance the operational usage and ergonomically meet end user requirements. Provided analytical support for the U.S. Army Landing Craft Utility (LCU) C4ISR/CEN verification surveys to U.S. Army Tank-Automotive & Armaments Command (TACOM. Provided analytical documentation to support the conceptual C4ISR/CEN design for U.S Army Landing Craft Utility-2000 class vessel to U.S. Army Combined Arms Support Command (CASCOM) and U.S. Army Tank-Automotive & Armaments Command (TACOM) representatives during the initial material fielding meeting. Provided Standard Automated Logistic Tool Sets (SALTS) Technical and Administration support for U.S Army Watercraft account holders worldwide and coordinated any additional support with the Naval Supply Systems Command (NAVSUP).

title: Systems Engineer
description: For the Family of Beyond the line of Sight Terminals (FAB-T) project: * I completed Risk Reduction Prototype (RRP) Increment 2 within budget and ahead of schedule, saving one million dollars and three months time using Earned Value Management System (EVMS) at Boeing. * Lead the requirements management process to develop and provide comprehensive product strategy including technical readiness level (TRL) to the FAB-T program. * Collaborated and completed FAB-T system requirements, human factors and ergonomics (HF&E) trade study process (benchmarking, best value) and final testing to get customer approvals. Performed multi-disciplinary trade studies and evaluated configuration alternatives for functional and spatial integration of FAB-T for Global Hawk Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (UAV). Used Rhapsody and V-model systems engineering and used service-oriented architecture approach. * Managed program risks and opportunities and provided Technical Readiness Level (TRL) details to the customer. * Provided modeling and CONOPS for fail safe designs on FAB-T INFOSEC cryptographic module to meet NSA information security assurance (IA) requirements of nuclear hardening and Tempest. For the Energy Smart Grid project: * Completed initial architecture and requirements study for the DoD customers. For the iGPS project: * Completed the network systems architecture, requirements and connectivity trades for the CONUS and OCONUS locations using LabNet, OPAA, VPN and VSF technologies. * Completed network element management system (NMS) requirements and design using (1) What’s Up Gold, (2) PathView, (3) ACE Live 2100, (4) Cisco Works, (5) WireShark tools and others. * I completed IPv4 to IPv6 conversion and lab simulation study. For the i2e Global Maritime Solutions (GMS) * Strategy, Core technical requirements, small-boat detection risk analysis

title: Responsible Systems and Design Engineer
description: * Completed the system requirements, design and testing of the Time and Frequency Reference (TFR) HW module of the Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) and F-35 Communication Navigation and Interrogation (CNI) and Radar systems. Developed performance requirements, architecture, performing system trades, inter-segment link analysis, ICD, system capacity and coverage analysis, simulations, and testing to provide a unique TFR module design that is robust and provides accurate reference frequency and phase noise to meet demanding needs of SATCOM and other military waveforms. * I completed Systems Test design for Dual Channel RF Receiver module of F-22/A Raptor aircraft (DXCVR RF) * Designed cryptographic modules and provided Multi Level Security (MLS) for F-22/A systems. Completed a number of mathematical models, simulated the design, and performed design of experiments (DOE), and operational research to manufacture the products.

title: Sr. Systems Integration Engineer
description: Systems integration and network engineer with duties that primarily consisted of analyzing existing enterprise and producing formal recommendations for improving existing hardware, software, and general design to improve performance and maintain proper security throughout the client’s infrastructure. Tasks also include coordinating and reviewing business model and methodologies to enhance workplace efficiency and proficiency. Knowledge used required knowledge of the complexities of NGA’s diverse enterprise along with current and future demands to meet formal, long term requirements and short term needs in an ever changing environment. In late 2007 to 2008, led major review of ASP/ISP infrastructure and resources across many organizations and groups that promulgated events that led to structural changes that exist today. Assisted in the development and integration of operational sustainment and support technologies and staff. Was liaison to the netowork operation center staff and trainer for Tier 2 and 3 staff with proprietary implementation of network monitoring tools. Key member of small team that led the consolidation effort for the entire ECI (Enterprise Controlled Interface). Hundreds of entities and multifarious systems were reviewed in place with coordination activities to properly transition to consolidate security across all three domains. This included the production of detailed diagrams (As-Is and To-Be), transition documents, coordination with security and the entities themselves, vetting checklists, and presenting at formal board reviews. Key component of Decommission and Disposal effort essential for the secure and documented removal of over 200 systems that involved many thousands of pieces of hardware, software, and other related items. This required maintaining accountability, tracking resources, meeting deadlines, and presenting to the Engineering Review Board for compliance.

title: Sr. Network Engineer
description: Primary duty consists of maintaining continuity between tier2 and tier3 teams as a technical liaison while supporting the normal operations of both tier groups on TCP/IP, ATM, Gigabit Ethernet, and LAN/WAN networking resolutions. Researched and development to improve network performance and higher level troubleshooting is performed for the tier 3 group. Training personnel and assisting in specialized areas with the tier 2 network group is done while passing on technical updates from tier 3 to the second group. Responsibility is also to proactively pass on updates pertinent to network related issues to both teams and address any changes for the middle tier group passed on from the upper level support unit. Network maintenance and troubleshooting is done on a Cisco based network that features TACLANE and FASTLANE crypto units. Cisco products were primarily in the 6500, 4500, 4000, 7200, 2900, 2600, and 1700 series families. Peregrine is the trouble ticket system for network problems/updates with HPOV and WhatsUpGold as the primary network monitoring platforms. Development projects typically included the use and/or development of technologies such as multicasting, QOS, and encryption software and hardware. Demonstrated effective use of mixed environment of Cat OS and IOS command line, EIGRP and OSPF routing, and ATM and Ethernet technologies.

title: Systems Engineer
description: Involved in reviewing and correcting engineering orders for engineers that remote sites will use to implement solutions to enhance or upgrade network capabilities. This typically included ways to facilitate increases in WAN bandwidth and network throughput. Performed requirements analysis, architecture assessments, readiness and transitions evaluations, schedule and risk assessments for multifarious projects that included SIPRNET, JWICS, GIG BE modifications. Analyzed network request and created or modified solutions utilizing various routers and switches (Cisco 3550 EMI/SMI switches, 2600 series routers, 2900 series switches, and Marconi ASX 1000, 1200, and ESR 5000 switches), cryptologic devices (KG-250, KIV-19, and KG-75), and an array of network hardware (media converters, hubs, etc.). Knowledge of WAN links (OC-3, DS3, T-1, fractional T-1, etc), the interfaces, and the media types associated with those technologies has also been demonstrated in performing everyday tasks. Part of a small deployment team that configures and troubleshoots all aspect of layer two and three processes for imagery circuits across the US (30% travel) following pre-stage testing and development at a primary test site. This usually consists of routing with OSPF and RIP. title: Sr. Network Engineer
description: Member of a small team involved in large-scale project to address scalability and performance issues for entire FBI network nationwide, entailing the management of millions of dollars worth of large Cisco switches and high performance routers. Provided analyses, system performance assessment, and design planning and implementation. Supported project at FBI headquarters to design, configure, and install network composed of all manner of Cisco equipment including new products like the CE7305 and CE565 content engines. SME for content design, configuration, and implementation, of Cisco Content Network Devices. Monitoring and updating field office and core network Cisco 6509, 2924, 2620, 1760, 4507, 7204, 7305, CE565, and 515E devices. Network engineering/integration support for communications and network systems for remote field offices and the network core. Also update aspects of the core design with effective use of ether channels and UDLD protocol. Properly allocated and addressed IP design issues to allow for proper size, scalability, and continuity of design. Network core design modifications for efficient L3 backbone and distributed network layout using Cisco best practices also accomplished. Gigabit Ethernet migration from 10/100 to 10/100/1000 performed, and ATM LAN/WAN technology utilizing variations of single and multimode fiber with SC and MTRJ connections. Test and troubleshooting of WAN and LAN connectivity between field office sites and headquarters. This included necessary network outages (with approval), monitoring trouble ticket status and relaying the pertinent information to all the concerned parties, and providing Sprint the changes and additions for WAN interfaces, addressing, and all routing. Defined requirements and performed analysis to develop LAN/WAN interfaces, generate engineering documentation, project plans/schedules, weekly reports, and engineering design documents to support a transition to an operational environment.

title: Network Support Engineer
description: Network Engineer in a system manager position for contract to monitor, troubleshoot, and support large networks using HPOV, MRTG, and UNIX. Functioned primarily as Tier 2 Network Operations Support. Duties include monitoring and troubleshooting OC-3 and OC-12 feeds, router and switch interfaces, network hubs, bridges, NT and UNIX terminals, and all related transmission media. Monitored and remotely restarted IDS devices (RealSecure and NetRanger). Statistical data was also compiled using performance monitoring tools and relayed to more senior engineers and placed in various reports. Assisted in the management of existing and new Windows 2000 account activation/deactivation, and permissions. Installed and configured Cisco 2900 series, 3550EMI, 3550SMI, and 4507R switched networks. Configured and managed 1760 and 2620 routers. Gigabit Ethernet migration performed transitioning from fast ethernet using 4507 switches also performed. Assisted in installation of new PC’s, fiber optic and Cat 5 cabling, fiber optic transceivers, and hubs on work site. Evaluation and necessary resync of various cryptographic devices. Used Remedy trouble ticket system, LanLog, and Access for technical documentation also. Functioned as primary technical interface to customer for providing technical status of the network and all pertinent sensors monitored.

title: CTM2
description: Position: Cryptologic Technician Maintenance-3 years with NEC9295 (WAN Management) 6 Years working with electronics, networks, software installations and configurations, TEMPEST, and cryptologic technology for government and civilian agencies on both small and large scale projects (DIA, DOD/HDS Corp., Motorola, etc.). Awarded Joint Commendation medal for services rendered with DIA as a CTM. 3 years experience supervising mid-level communication systems installation projects that included troubleshooting data and analog circuits, repairing communication lines, front and back-end support for onboard configuration changes. Awarded Navy Achievement Medal and Flag Letter of Commendation for outstanding performance of technical support duties on USS Juneau and CINPACFLEET for troubleshooting and repairing mission critical primary and secondary communication circuits during Middle East peacekeeping operations afloat in 1997. Installed LAN's and satellite systems for CINPACFLEET warships which included 10BaseT and 10BaseFL LAN runs with proper termination techniques, ensuring use of proper system identification numbers, azimuth and elevation settings for satellites, installing fiber optic transceivers, testing for signal attenuation with spectrum analyzers and time domain reflectometers, and building data cables. Also read wiring diagrams for fabrication of maintenance breakout panels and performed continuity checks. Performed system installations and demonstrations of classified automated computer systems for personnel in the FBI, CIA, DIA, and military.

title: Director
description: This is a 106-unit townhome association in northwest Los Angeles County. Total valuation is approximately $30 million. Key Success Factors (KSF's) include: Acting in a fiduciary capacity, work constructively with other directors to maintain the architectural integrity of the complex; communicate effectively with homeowners/residents to ensure enforcement of rules; work with, and direct, the management company to ensure that all applicable laws and ordinances are followed. Directors are also responsible for the preparation of annual operating and capital budgets. Also served on the board from January 1989 to June 2007. Participated in the reconstruction of the complex following the 1994 Northridge Earthquake, a $14-million project.

title: Lead Principal/INFOSEC Engineer
description: • Developed configuration management plan and processes for a Navy Integrated Development Environment • Developed Information Assurance Strategy for Navy classified project • Developed System Security Authorization Agreement for Navy Landing Craft Air Cushion cost model • Provided IA support to Program Executive Officer for Integrated Warfare Systems in support of Common Enterprise Display System. This included revising the Information Assurance Strategy • Developed Information Support Plan for PEO IWS 6.0 Common Enterprise Display System • Developed Modular Open Systems Approach (MOSA) Report for Navy Maritime Pre-positioning Force (Future). Served as Chief Scientist/SME for MOSA activities for this program. • Developed System Security Authorization Agreement for Naval Sea Systems Command Ship Design Laboratory Unclassified Network • Providing Information Assurance Support to Naval Facilities Engineering Command (NAVFAC) including representing NAVFAC at Virtual SYSCOM forums (Platform IT Working Group, IA Technical Advisory Board, Navy End-to-End IPT Governance and CM Working Groups), reviewing draft DoD policies for NAVFAC impact, developing NAVFAC tailored policies, conducting Security Test and Evaluation, reviewing certification and accreditation packages for both Platform IT and non Platform IT systems, proposing security metrics. Providing feedback to IA Technical Advisory Board background papers on Service-Oriented Architecture. Working on enterprise security documentation for industrial control systems to include security guide (including metrics and risk management), configuration management plan, incident response plan, continuous monitoring guide, information assurance strategy. • Elected as a Defense Group Associate Fellow for Information Assurance. Worked on a project concerning Return on Investment for Security. • Led worldwide team performing revision of security section of IEEE Draft Standard P23026

title: Full Spectrum Cyberspace Planning and Targeting Officer
description: Developed the Planning and Targeting Processes through which a Joint Force Headquarters Cyberspace (JFHQ-C) would support of the Theater Special Operation Components (TSOC). Responsible for planning full spectrum cyberspace operations in support of TSOC operations. Provided full spectrum cyber operations planning and cyber scenario development in support of large-scale exercises at the Geographic Combatant Commands. • Chosen as the G2 representative to the operation planning team (OPT) that developed a JFHQ-C planning process and the boards, bureaus, councils, cells, and working groups that the JFHQ-C utilizes to provide full spectrum cyber operations to TSOC forces. • Developed the JFHQ-C targeting process and wrote the standard operating procedures (SOP) for JFHQ-C to provide full spectrum cyber operations in support of TSOC forces. • Chosen as the G2 representative to the OPT that developed how a Cyber Task Force will provide command and control of the Cyber Mission Teams (CMT) and Cyber Protection Teams (CPT). • Developed the targeting process that provided Special Operations Forces with full spectrum cyberspace operations. • Supported SOCEUR with education and detailed planning for full spectrum cyber operations. • Supported SOCPAC detailed planning that resulted in an approved CYBERPAC Cyber Effects Request Form (CERF). • Lead the Target Development Working Group responsible for conducting targeting for full spectrum cyber operations in support of SOCOM and the TSOCs. • Provided scenario development and full spectrum cyber operations planning in support of SOCEUR and EUCOM exercise GAUNLET CHALLENGE that resulted in the incorporation of cyberspace operations over the Joint IO Range in support of the exercise. • Provided scenario development and full spectrum cyber operations planning in support of SOCPAC and PACOM exercise TEMPEST WIND that resulted in the incorporation of cyberspace operations over the Joint IO in support of the exercise.

title: Special Intelligence Communications Officer
description: HEADQUARTERS MARINE CORPS INTELLIGENCE DEPARTMENT, WASHINGTON, DC Charged to locate and manage Top Secret certified bandwidth for the 2009 Marine Corps surge to Afghanistan. Tasked with the development of a concept of operations and fielding plan for a special intelligence payload for airborne platforms. As the subject matter expert on Marine ground Electronic Warfare, charged with leading stakeholders in developing the Marine Corps’ EW requirements for the years up to 2025. • Led the four person team that was able to meet the Marine Corps’ Afghan surge additional requirements of Top Secret satellite bandwidth by leveraging partnerships with NSA, DIA, the SECDEF’s ISR Task Force, and Army INSCOM. • Delivered a concept of operations for an airborne system with a special intelligence payload with a fielding plan scheduled for a 2010 Afghan deployment. • Led the Marine Ground EW Stakeholders in writing the Marine Corps EW 2025 Vision Concept of Operations. • Created the case study and requirements for a simulated war game scenario that allowed for the validation and continuation of a small and elite intelligence unit.

title: Firepower Control Team Leader
description: 4TH AIR NAVAL GUNFIRE LIAISON COMPANY, MARINE FORCES RESERVE, WEST PALM BEACH, FL Specializing in the coordination of artillery, naval gunfire and close air support (CAS) for the U.S. Marine Corps, U.S. Army, and allied foreign armed forces. Firepower Control Team Leader - Captain Tasked with being the subject matter expert in Fire Support to Marine Corps units, as well as U.S. Army and foreign military units. Led teams from five to 12 Marines in supporting Iraqi operations in Al Anbar province during the 2006 Surge. Leveraged relationships with Marine, Army, and Air Forces officers in order to ensure that all operations had the necessary air and fire support. Required to be certified to call in air strikes as a Joint Terminal Attack Controller (JTAC) and meet biannual requirements for proficiency. • Developed and executed the Air and Fire Support Plans for the first successful MNC-I level fuel convoy from Ramadi in the west to Bajyi in the north via Baghdad, that resulted in over 20 trucks delivering more than 10,000 gallons of fuel. • Wrote and published the handbook used in all future MNC-I level Ramadi to Bajyi fuel convoys that included POC information, call signs, and radio frequencies for all ground and air units with responsibilities along the route, that allowed for nine future convoys to deliver over 250,000 gallons of fuel to the Al Anbar province. • Built and leveraged relationships with Army and Air Force pilots in the central and northern sectors of Iraq that resulted in air support to Marine fuel convoys when outside of Marine areas of operation. • Analyzed and managed Iraqi army requirements for air and fire support that allowed 1st Brigade, 7th Iraqi Army to conduct its first brigade level operation.

title: Signal Intelligence and Ground Electronic Warfare Officer
description: Provided planning and mission support to Marine units in Afghanistan as executive officer of a Marine detachment during a seven-month deployment. Managed and was accountable for millions of dollars of TS/SCI collection and communication equipment used to support combat operations throughout the AOR simultaneously. Hand selected as the first Radio Battalion Officer to support an Army Special Forces team during a weeklong area reconnaissance mission. Provided SIGINT to the Targeting board in Iraq, in support of successful operations against High Value Targets. • Developed intelligence when supporting Army Special Forces, enabling successful Marine ground force operations. • Exploited target reliance on certain communication mediums to develop techniques in support of Marine ground forces operations. • Developed controls for TS/SCI collection and communication equipment accountability that allowed these sensitive assets to be used simultaneously throughout the AOR without any losses. • Built and leveraged relationships with NSA and Army SIGINT units that resulted in faster development and greater depth of intelligence products.

title: IT SPECIALIST (INFOSEC)
company: Pacific Air Force (PACAF), U.S. Air Force
description: Serve as the information management / information technology (IM/IT) technical expert and Information Assurance Manager (IAM) responsible for information security and certification and accreditation (C&A) for PACAF A6 enterprise information systems throughout the PACAF AOR. Provide program development and oversight for confidentiality, integrity and availability of systems, networks and data through planning, analysis development, maintenance and enhancement of information security programs, policies, procedures and tools. - Serve as a senior IA consultant for PACAF/A6 Computer Systems Flight (CSF) and staff, analyze and resolve difficult problems or issues, conducts special studies and make recommendations on new approach to delivery services. - Develop and provide application and information systems security principles, policies, processes and procedures for use and management of systems, networks and data. - Perform on-site studies covering theater wide information technology security status. - Evaluate existing systems and capabilities and perform cost benefit analysis to determine way ahead to enhance mission systems security performance. - Plan and conduct on-site security reviews for installed systems and networks and recommend new or revised security measures and countermeasures as required. - Responsible for managing C&A and guidance using Enterprise Mission Assurance Support Service (eMASS), Enterprise Information Technology Data Repository (EITDR), Task Management Tool (TMT) and Enterprise SharePoint. - Provide guidance, training and assistance to personnel, team leads and coordinators responsible for C&A artifacts including Configuration Management, Change Control, Incident Response and Contingency and Business Continuity Planning etc. - Provide IA processes and procedures to streamline and improve efficiency of the IA mission. - Provided IA training coordination and support for DoD 8570 certification and continuing education requirements.

title: Principal Information Security Analyst
description: Perform the following; design, test, implement, and manage Department of Defense (DoD) secure networks and information systems (IS); involved in a wide range of DoD information systems (IS) security issues including U.S. Army Pacific Information assurance (IA) program management, IA vulnerability management (IAVM) scans, policy, certification & accreditation, exercise support, protected distribution systems (PDS), IA and security training, and the command inspection programs. Review and recommend communications requirements, customer coordination, DoD Information Assurance Certification and Accreditation Process (DIACAP) package technical support, tracking, training, and Designated Approval Authority coordination activities. Advise and assist government of hardware/software tools that provide increased efficiency and productivity in mission and IA Program. Perform research into various regulations, policies, procedures, and instructions to provide guidance to network owners, managers, support staff, information management officers (IMOs) and users. Experienced with IA compliance inspections, reviews and reporting to include Department of the Army Inspector General (DAIG) IA Compliance Inspection, Command Cyber Readiness Inspection (CCRI) performed by DISA and Higher HQ Staff Assistance Visits (SAVs). - Managed and coordinated the IA effort for the organization to be the first unit to pass the DAIG IA Compliance Inspection. - Managed the successful IA efforts for organization and sister units to pass multiple CCRI's.

title: Lead Senior Secure Systems Engineer
description: Senior Information Assurance Consultant for the USARPAC Information Assurance Program Manager (IAPM) to the Commander 78th Signal Battalion and the 58th and 78th Signal Battalions IA operations support contract teams. Manage, review, and evaluate the work of all personnel working on the contract in Japan. Ensure personnel are performing as required and provide training requirements and weekly, monthly reports to the contract company as well as the Government COR. Responsible for all aspects of the DIACAP Certification and Accreditation (C&A) process for all Army units in Japan. Review and process subordinate and tenant unit Authority to Connect (ATC) and Authority to Operate (ATO) packages for USARPAC Designated Approving Authority (DAA). Track DIACAP packages submitted by the DAA to the Certification Authority Representative (CAR) for Department of the Army, Chief Information Officer/G6 (CIO/G6) approval. Manage and track IA workflow via automated means such as Enterprise Share Point or Intranet sites and repositories.

title: Senior Systems Administrator
description: Install, support and manage computer systems and wide area network equipment in support of various joint and bilateral military exercises in Japan and Korea to include Ulchi Focus Lens (UFL), Yama Sakura (YS), Reception, Staging and Onward Integration (RSOI) among others. Provide on-site support of equipment including computers, routers, switches, voice over IP (VOIP) phones and VTC equipment, etc.

title: Information Technology Specialist (GS12)
description: Senior Information Technology Specialist and Systems Administrator for the United States Army Japan (USARJ) Deputy Chief of Staff for Operation (DCSOPS), Command Operations Center (COC) and Emergency Action Console (EAC) for the DCSOPS/G3. title: IT Specialist (PLCYPLN / INFOSEC)
company: U.S. Army Pacific (USARPAC) Cyber Security Program Management Office (CSPMO)
description: Serve on the U. S. Army Pacific Command (USARPAC) Information Assurance (IA) Team providing direct support to the USARPAC IA Program Manager on matters of network security and the command Information Assurance Vulnerability Management (IAVM) program. The position plans, designs, develops, implements, and manages Information Assurance (IA) programs that meet current and future business requirements; designed to anticipate, assess, and minimize system vulnerabilities; and ensures the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of automated systems, networks in accordance with current DoD, DA and USARPAC IA policies. - Independently identifies the need for and develops new policy or recommends changes to existing Department of the Army policies, standards and procedures for managing strategic or tactical automation and Information Assurance. - Provides advice and guidance pertinent to Information Assurance program policies, guides, and standard operating procedures during all stages of the automation process. - Administers programs which address Information Assurance operations and readiness.

title: IT SPECIALIST (INFOSEC)
company: Pacific Air Force (PACAF), U.S. Air Force
description: Serve as the information management / information technology (IM/IT) technical expert and Information Assurance Manager (IAM) responsible for information security and certification and accreditation (C&A) for PACAF A6 enterprise information systems throughout the PACAF AOR. Provide program development and oversight for confidentiality, integrity and availability of systems, networks and data through planning, analysis development, maintenance and enhancement of information security programs, policies, procedures and tools. - Serve as a senior IA consultant for PACAF/A6 Computer Systems Flight (CSF) and staff, analyze and resolve difficult problems or issues, conducts special studies and make recommendations on new approach to delivery services. - Develop and provide application and information systems security principles, policies, processes and procedures for use and management of systems, networks and data. - Perform on-site studies covering theater wide information technology security status. - Evaluate existing systems and capabilities and perform cost benefit analysis to determine way ahead to enhance mission systems security performance. - Plan and conduct on-site security reviews for installed systems and networks and recommend new or revised security measures and countermeasures as required. - Responsible for managing C&A and guidance using Enterprise Mission Assurance Support Service (eMASS), Enterprise Information Technology Data Repository (EITDR), Task Management Tool (TMT) and Enterprise SharePoint. - Provide guidance, training and assistance to personnel, team leads and coordinators responsible for C&A artifacts including Configuration Management, Change Control, Incident Response and Contingency and Business Continuity Planning etc. - Provide IA processes and procedures to streamline and improve efficiency of the IA mission. - Provided IA training coordination and support for DoD 8570 certification and continuing education requirements.

title: Principal Information Security Analyst
description: Perform the following; design, test, implement, and manage Department of Defense (DoD) secure networks and information systems (IS); involved in a wide range of DoD information systems (IS) security issues including U.S. Army Pacific Information assurance (IA) program management, IA vulnerability management (IAVM) scans, policy, certification & accreditation, exercise support, protected distribution systems (PDS), IA and security training, and the command inspection programs. Review and recommend communications requirements, customer coordination, DoD Information Assurance Certification and Accreditation Process (DIACAP) package technical support, tracking, training, and Designated Approval Authority coordination activities. Advise and assist government of hardware/software tools that provide increased efficiency and productivity in mission and IA Program. Perform research into various regulations, policies, procedures, and instructions to provide guidance to network owners, managers, support staff, information management officers (IMOs) and users. Experienced with IA compliance inspections, reviews and reporting to include Department of the Army Inspector General (DAIG) IA Compliance Inspection, Command Cyber Readiness Inspection (CCRI) performed by DISA and Higher HQ Staff Assistance Visits (SAVs). - Managed and coordinated the IA effort for the organization to be the first unit to pass the DAIG IA Compliance Inspection. - Managed the successful IA efforts for organization and sister units to pass multiple CCRI's.

title: Lead Senior Secure Systems Engineer
description: Senior Information Assurance Consultant for the USARPAC Information Assurance Program Manager (IAPM) to the Commander 78th Signal Battalion and the 58th and 78th Signal Battalions IA operations support contract teams. Manage, review, and evaluate the work of all personnel working on the contract in Japan. Ensure personnel are performing as required and provide training requirements and weekly, monthly reports to the contract company as well as the Government COR. Responsible for all aspects of the DIACAP Certification and Accreditation (C&A) process for all Army units in Japan. Review and process subordinate and tenant unit Authority to Connect (ATC) and Authority to Operate (ATO) packages for USARPAC Designated Approving Authority (DAA). Track DIACAP packages submitted by the DAA to the Certification Authority Representative (CAR) for Department of the Army, Chief Information Officer/G6 (CIO/G6) approval. Manage and track IA workflow via automated means such as Enterprise Share Point or Intranet sites and repositories.

title: Information Technology Specialist (GS12)
description: Senior Information Technology Specialist and Systems Administrator for the United States Army Japan (USARJ) Deputy Chief of Staff for Operation (DCSOPS), Command Operations Center (COC) and Emergency Action Console (EAC) for the DCSOPS/G3. Responsibilities included duties as Staff Action Officer for planning, coordinating, and implementing a wide variety of Army, Department of Defense, Joint and Bilateral information technology projects and programs. Managed all aspects of automation operations and security located in the COC and G3. Project manager for a multi-million dollar COC upgrade and expansion to meet DA, Joint and Bilateral mission requirements. Applied project management principles to ensure project success.

title: Security Architect
description: Applies strong technical skills and experience to recommend, implement, support, improve and operate information security controls. Develops secure systems and network architectures and assists other teams in securing their architectures at the logical and physical levels. Supplies expertise to management, business areas, and IT teams in risk assessment as well as implementation of appropriate data security controls and monitoring. Reviews/evaluates systems and processes for compliance to Ally information security standards, including compliance aspects of GLBA, EU Data Protection Directive, Sarbanes-Oxley and other relevant laws and regulations. Provides thought leadership by identifying new information security threats, emerging technologies, and counter-measures. Supports IT-related projects as an information security subject matter expert, providing support throughout their life cycle. Assess, report on and make recommendations regarding current and proposed architectures, strategies and systems.

title: Principal System Engineer
description: Technical management lead for the Security Integrated Product Team (IPT) responsible for execution, and provided leadership and management of assigned personnel within Security IPT. Collaborated with other IPT leads regarding security and interoperability requirements, issue resolution, and compliance to established Department of Defense (DoD)/Intelligence Community security directives, instructions, and guidelines. Managed program resources ranging from $300K to six million dollars, and provided technical program execution status to Program and Technical Management. Interfaced directly with customer regarding system security, and provided Subject Matter Expert (SME) consultation to internal programs. Developed security compliant architectures, responded to statements of work, and provided cost and milestone for proposal responses. Performed system security test development, execution and reporting; risk management, security configuration guideline development and compliance reviews, vulnerability scans and mitigation; and configuration management control (security representative). • Researched, developed, and directed approach in maintaining the FIPS 140-2 cryptographic certification for OpenSSL to a new processing environment without the need for recertification saving the program $100K in direct costs and a 6-8 month schedule slip. • Managed and directed security compliance efforts of a non-traditional prototype wireless IP radio system development effort garnering Army approval; when deployed extends the tactical battlefield’s IP network. • Authored, developed, and taught a DoD security compliance course focusing on compliance efforts within the systems engineering V-development process including future changes to NIST 800-53 and Risk Management Framework, resulting in engineering leads understanding their roles and responsibilities (in collaboration with the Security IPT) in meeting current and emerging DoD security compliance requirements.

description: Managed the Directorate of Information Management and Chief Information Officer Reserve Program, and supervised 25 Reserve personnel assigned to the program. title: Senior Staff Security Engineer
description: Technical security management lead for the Joint Strike Fighter (JSF) ground based systems including those used to support mission planning, training, logistics, and maintenance of the JSF. Provided SME consultation to development teams, and interfaced directly with customer in regards to system security matters. Performed technical design data and information review according to Department of State, Commerce, and Defense requirements for appropriate release to foreign countries involved with the JSF. Performed anti-tamper techniques, technology, tactics and procedures according to established standards ensuring JSF data and technology were resistant to reverse engineering. • Authored International Traffic in Arms Regulations (ITAR) document, gained approval in less than 30 days allowing for key exchange of technical information between the United States, United Kingdom, and other JSF Partner Countries. • Assisted in developing the JSF Ground-Based security architecture, architecture compliant with DoD, Ministry of Defense, and other Partner Countries’ security compliance regulations, standards, or guidelines. • Led compliance requirements development and validation efforts across all JSF ground-based platforms, ensuring security was designed into platforms minimizing compliance issues and potential system re-designs.

title: Senior Systems Security Engineer
description: Managed Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Privacy and Security Rule Task Order, and directed 10 people supporting the effort. Performed security and vulnerability assessments, developed security architectures based on customer requirements, taught security courses, and supported proposal development. • Authored HIPAA GAP assessment used as framework for Privacy and Security Rule assessments, accepted as an official guide when performing GAP assessments. • Developed Oracle database security plan and procedures used in performing on site security assessments and authored software assurance standards, both efforts combined in fully assessing risk for customer, thus allowing for proper resourcing to mitigate risk. • Wrote requirements and security architecture allowing for exchange of information between different and divergent sensitivity levels increasing situational awareness to key decision makers.

title: CIO and Chief, IT Division
description: CIO and Chief of the IT Division, responsible for a 26 person government and contractor team charged with design, acquisition and implementation of a scalable and agile system consisting of UNCLASSIFIED, SECRET and TOP SECRET networks to host applications supporting the national effort to identify DoD missing personnel. Responsible for requirements analysis, development of IT strategy alternatives and the supporting budget estimates and spend plan necessary to meet the DPMO mission. Government Task Lead (GTL) for two contracts providing IT support, application development and the implementation of a geographical information system (GIS) for DPMO intelligence analysts. Subject matter expert for all IT acquisition and technology matters.

title: Executive Director
description: Principal Engineer responsible for the planning, design, test, evaluation and acquisition of hardware, software and networking technology to support the Theater C4I network of an international network for a Joint Command. Key functional areas supported include: • Network Architecture • Information Assurance • Department of State, Department of Defense and Intelligence Community Special Security Requirements • Approved NSA and NIST Communications Security Solutions and Policies, including Communications Security (COMSEC) • DoD Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) policies, equipment, applications and procedures • Multi-domain “Trusted” Systems and Technologies • Satellite, radio and optical communications systems • Continuity of Operations Planning, Disaster Avoidance and Recovery.

title: Partner and Co-Owner
description: Co-owner of a small 20 person engineering firm with contracts supporting OASD C3I, US Army CECOM, DISA, DIA, NSA and DOJ responsible for the architecture and implementation of classified, unclassified and coalition wide area networks supporting command, control, intelligence and law enforcement requirements in overseas locations with interfaces to partner nations and other US Govt agencies. Reseller of special TEMPEST security and information technology equipment.

title: Communications Electronics Engineer
description: Command, Control, Communications systems starting at White Sands Missile Range where I was involved in the testing of medium and high altitude air defense weapon systems and their associated tactical command and control systems along with their supporting telecommunications networks. Also served as both a Signal officer and C-E responsible for the design and implementation of communications and electronics systems in Berlin, Germany during the cold war supporting special systems, followed by three assignments in the Pentagon where I was responsible for the development and implementation of management information systems and networks, on the Army Staff followed by a tour with the Office of the Assistant Secretary of the Army for Manpower and Reserve Affairs and finally with the Office of the Chief of Staff Army progressively developing larger scale management information systems and executive information systems to support the senior management of the Army Staff.

title: IT Security CSIRT / SOC Manager
description: Managed and provided guidance to staff of seventeen in a 24x7 environment. Established procedures and controls for SOC. Security project management for projects as diverse as building of a new fault tolerant data center to corporate communications through new media such as face book and MySpace. Service level agreements Staff training on security compliance, audit, incident response and paths of escalation. Developed team lead concept to further increase efficiency. Assisted in the development and execution of departmental strategic plans and objectives. Worked on development of new Security Operations facility encompassing evidence storage, forensic lab, staff ergonomics, technical requirements, system and monitoring center design. PCI, HIPAA, SOX, Privacy and CMS Compliance. ISO 25000:2005 Technical project management Liaison between multiple business and technology areas, assisting internally and externally with the assessment, procurement and implementation of new technology security solutions. Worked with diverse business owners and other security groups to facilitate penetration testing to ensure the security of systems and applications, in both corporate and external vender networks. Established comprehensive change management procedures, policies and controls. Corporate security assurance program. Established training requirements for continued accreditation of incident response team. Established controls for the identification and removal of bots from internal systems. Rogue device detection and response on all corporate and new acquisition networks. Document problems, resolutions, and post mortems to senior executive management and other key stakeholders. Log consolidation of all network devices, applications and systems. Assisted in the review of new acquisitions security posture. Contributed to corporate security awareness program.

title: Senior Network Engineer
description: Network security engineer. Designed secure, reliable national and international communication strategies, implemented security technologies. Network engineer responsible for corporate LAN and WAN including global access for 100,000 plus user base in 10 countries. Responsible for all routing and switching equipment, design, and debugging. Installation and maintenance of multiple PIX firewalls, including all NAT mapping and conduits, in failover configuration. Implementation of Cisco VPN encryption technologies, Router IOS to IOS, IOS to Concentrators, and Remote Client to Concentrator, and Concentrator to Concentrator. Installation client remote site networks, Gigabit Ethernet, DS3s and T1s, and VPN connections. Responsible for insuring all equipment IOS levels are current and documented, with emphasis on vendor security advisories. Design and documentation of corporate LAN/WAN upgrades. Responsible for new project design, implementation, and documentation, with strong emphasis on research, security and testing prior to implementation within the production environment. Schedule maintenance windows, document planned changes and completed work to upper management. Document problems, resolutions, and post mortems to upper management. Responsible for site installation, maintenance and upgrades of remote CPE facilities. Responsible for application of Autonomous system Number from ARIN and IP address block assignments. Designed and installed multiple instances of dual homed redundancy with BGP. Authored network outage notification and change control documentation. Authored and maintain all network documentation Implementation of Cisco TACACS+ Authentication servers used for router, switch and user VPN authentication. Implementation of Radius based redundant authentication for remote client access.

title: Senior overhead collection analyst
description: Actively involved in the operations of the target country's office by performing fusion analysis and drafted vital reports of time-sensitive data in support of Fleet and National consumers. Monitored and investigated issues with the collection platforms including any unknown possible cyber attacks. Maintained working relationship with contacts in various government organizations including DIA, ONI and NSA . Maintained and updated technical databases and libraries with new signals of interest. Led the junior operator in the analysis of more than 4,000 signals of interest and disseminated more than 400 reports. At a Navy Information Operations Detachment overseas function as the senior Fleet Support Operator and Leading Petty Officer which maintains communications with US assets within the 6th Fleet Area of Responsibility and am a vital liaison with coalition ships. Assisted the OPSEC coordinator in reviewing security logs and conducting routine OPSEC and INFOSEC investigations and assisted in OPSEC evaluations and exercises. Maintained Information Assurance standards and conducted training for IA. Developed tactics, techniques and procedures (TTP) for ensuring positions were properly manned and operated using the appropriate tools. Monitored and researched various target command and control communications systems for developing target packages and reports. Experience with developing information operations (IO) strategic plan and course of action (COA). BUILDER operator and subject matter expert at current command, a program used for creating Radio Frequency Mission Planning for customers around the world. Disseminated more than 800 reports to international customers. Conducted electromagnetic/radio frequency (EM/RF) searches and collection. Experience using and setting up wireless LAN and Bluetooth technologies. Experience and working knowledge of TEMPEST. Assisted in producing after action reports following intelligence operations.

Trained 12 personnel on specific job qualifications Promoted to the divisions Leading Petty Officer and was responsible for the management of all watch standers in the division, ensuring all tasking is completed. Combined and rewrote 35 Standard Operating Procedures for two different divisions. Operations

title: Special Security Officer
description: Provides high-level security guidance, sustainability and supervisory support to the AFCENT FWD Deployed Special Security Office (SSO); administers the SCI security program (personnel, physical, information security, industrial security, information assurance) to thirty three (33) regional AFCENT subordinate SCIFs located in the CENTCOM AOR (Qatar, Kuwait, Afghanistan, United Arab Emirates, Oman, and Iraq). Key responsibilities consist of the following: Ensures the development, documentation, and presentation of official SSO and Information Systems Security training (ISSO) for 66 government and military Special Security Representatives (SSRs) and over 5k personnel. Performs risk assessments and security configuration reviews. Executes cross domain file transfers using specialized software tools, system and procedures IAW regulatory requirements. Conducts classification investigations for security violations and incidents on networks. Manages MILCON SCIF construction projects from conceptualization to implementation based on ICD 705 and DoD 5105.21 volume 2. Reviews building design plans/blueprints and provide risk assessments for constructing new SCIFs and Tactical SCIFs (TSCIFs), review/prepare fixed facility checklist, Tempest Addendums and documentation for new SCIF accreditations. Conducts site security surveys, including compliance of technology equipment supporting SCIFs (e.g., access control, intrusion detection systems, locks, destruction devices, secure phones, etc.), prior to SCIF accreditation and during Staff Assistant Visits (SAVs). Manages the access control systems (badge system, intrusion detection system). Establishes co-utilization agreements with coalition forces, Special Access Programs (SAPs) and other non-DoD organizations. Maintains/updates SCIF documentation (Fixed Facility Checklist, TEMPEST Addendum, risk management framework (RMF) for information systems, etc.) as required. Oversees personnel security program.

title: Facility Security Officer (FSO)/Special Security Officer (SSO)
description: Serves as the Special Security Officer (SSO) for the Combined Joint Intelligence Operations Center, Afghanistan (CJIOC-A) in support of OEF. Supports USFOR-A in processing personnel investigations for special security clearance actions to include: Formulating and ensuring compliance with automated information systems security procedures, suggesting, implementing and monitoring compliance with the ISAF/USFOR-A special security policies and procedures. Responsible for proper physical security requirements of 1 permanent SCIF and 28 T-SCIFS through-out the RC-Capitol. Conducts and coordinates the training for all special security representatives in the RC-Capitol. Performs liaison with Government, NATO and industrial security officials throughout CENTCOM AOR. Supports collateral and higher access indoctrinations and badging for the ISAF/USFOR-A HQs.

title: Administrative Assistant
description: Provides administrative support to engineers and program analysts, prepareing correspondence, briefings and reports of a technical nature. Proofreads/edits correspondence and documents. Make domestic and international travel arrangements and process expense reports and associated forms, attends meetings and generate/distribute minutes, order and maintain office supplies. Administrative duties entail administrative support for scanning, faxing, copying, handling official mail, filing, and shredding documents. Support the management of Outlook calendars for senior personnel, and multiple conference rooms. Interacts with other administrative support personnel and provide "as needed" support to government program office, also serves as a purchasing agent. Assist facility security officer with JPAS and other routine security matters.

title: Administrative Office Supervisor/Assistant Security Manager
description: Developed and implemented policies and procedures for analyzing and evaluating the character, background, and history of employees, candidates for employment, and other persons having or proposed to be granted access to classified or other sensitive information, materials, or work sites. Responsible for the management and professional development of 9 Sailors in every facet of administration, supporting more than 600 enlisted personnel and 21 Officers. Responsibilities include direct administrative support for the Commanding Officer and the Executive Officer and providing front office support in the absence of the executive assistant. Also, works as the liaison with PSD, procurement and budget specialist, security manager, NSIPS manager, E-Leave, TWMS administrator.

title: Special Security Officer (SSO)/Security Manager/Personnel Security Manager
description: Managed 2 command’s sensitive compartmented information (SCI) personnel security programs. Identifed, prioritized and delegated work to assigned staff to ensure timely and efficient service to over 5000 SCI cleared personnel. Continuously provided feedback and training to leadership, subordinates, and staff members as required. Briefed and advised the Command’s Senior Leadership, Special Security Officer, and Personnel Chief on daily SSO matters and recommends solutions. Liaisoned with all Central Adjudication Facilities (CAFs) on all SCI reportable cases ensuring the CAF’s deadlines are met. Responsible for maintaining the command’s SCI derogatory case database and leading, advising, and supporting SSO on SCI eligibility and case options. Coordinated meetings, maintained suspense files and assisted personnel on derogatory cases for responses and PSAB’s. Managed SSO personnel security records and databases as required. Continue process of automating personnel security administrative tasks to reduce processing time. Review database records; make entries and changes as need. Review staff entries for accuracy. As the assistant command special security officer, led a five member joint service team responsible for accurately maintaining and controlling over 3000 SCI files for all command personnel local and globally while handling critical tasks with minimal assistance from superiors. Supported 2500 Special Operations Forces billets worldwide. Drafted and released over 600 SCI messages in support of Global War on Terror (GWOT) and Special Operation Forces (SOF) missions around the world ensuring real time information was disseminated in a timely manner. Responsible for 23 command sensitive compartmented information facilities (SCIF) locally and nationally.

title: Special Security Officer (SSO)/Security Manager/Personnel Security Manager con't
description: As a Physical Security officer directed the construction of over 9 SCIFs ensuring construction was completed in a timely manner and accreditations were approved. Managed a secure environment by ensuring compliance and implementation of all security regulations and operating procedures were followed via closed circuit television, unannounced entry/exit bag inspections, and various command walk-thru all departments. Received and transmitted classified mail; maintain document control; Manages SCI customer’s of the Defense Courier Service (DEFCOS) stations. COMSEC Custodian communications security hardware and software was delivered to customers locations; coordinated and tracked Actions when necessary; maintained hand receipts for document control. Provided hands-on support and management of all aspects of physical, technical, personnel, administrative and COMSEC security associated with Top Secret/SCI material for the command. Maintained document control accountability receipts, storing, safeguarding of classified materials. Managed security clearance investigations using the Joint Personnel Adjudication System (JPAS) administration and Defense Security Services. Provided support to executive leadership, scheduling and administrative support. Developed and implemented policies and procedures for analyzing and evaluating the character, background, and history of employees, candidates for employment, and other persons having or proposed to be granted access to classified or other sensitive information, materials, or work sites. Also, was responsible for the management and professional development of Sailors in every facet of administration. Responsibilities include direct administrative support for the Commanding Officer and the Executive Officer and providing front office support in the absence of the executive assistant. Also, worked as the liaison with Personnel Support Detachment(HR department), procurement and budget specialist, and security manager.

title: Administrative Office Manager/Special Security Officer
description: Implemented policies, procedures, standards, training, and methods for identifying and protecting information, personnel, property, facilities, operations, or material from unauthorized disclosure, misuse, theft, assault, vandalism, espionage, sabotage, or loss. Provided administrative assistance and security management to over 80 Sailors in multiple Middle East locations. Coordinated and forwards correspondence to appropriate office. Update the tracking system and suspense file as required. Reviews outgoing correspondence prepared by others for procedural and grammatical accuracy, conformant with general policy, and factual correctness. Develops, establishes, updates and maintain office procedures and records/files of various types to ensure effective and efficient operations of the command. Provides advice and guidance to staff on administrative, clerical and procedural.

Established and maintained all correspondence filing structure within the command.

title: Professor
description: Department Lead, Information Operations Designs, formats and teaches graduate level Information Assurance (IA), Information Operations (IO), and cyber courses. Serve as the college IO lead and Information, Warfare, and Military Strategy course manager. Teaches federal agencies the application of IA principles to meet agency mission and security needs while balancing risk. Provides technical and policy based IA advice to federal agencies. Establish long range, intermediate and short range plans. Research, develop and instructs National Security Agency (NSA) certified graduate and distance learning curricula for National War College, Eisenhower School, iCollege, and other Department of Defense (DoD) institutions. Graduate school professor who teaches in seven courses to include: 1. Continuity of Operations (COO), 2. Cyber Security for Information Leaders (SEC), 3. Critical Information and Infrastructure Protection (CIP), 4. Industrial Control System Security at Air Force Institute of Technology 5. Information Assurance and Critical Infrastructure Protection (AII), 6. Information, Warfare, and Military Strategy (IWS Course Leader), and 7. Terrorism and Crime in Cyberspace (TCC).

title: Sr. Technology & Innovation Officer, Project ECHO
description: After spending two years building up Project ECHO's IT capacity in application development, online training, IT project management and Help Desk support, this new position enables me to now place a far greater focus on exploring advanced and emerging technologies that can be architected to enhance the scalability, security and sustainability of the Project ECHO model. -Perform systems engineering analysis in: Big Data infrastructure, data science (utilizing R), mobile and cloud-based applications, video and telecommunications technology, massively open online course (MOOC) development and deployment of the ECHO model into low-bandwidth rural and medically underserved areas throughout the world. -Research and evaluate options for Business Associates Agreement(s), Service Level Agreements and Data Sharing Agreements with outside companies that can handle Project ECHO's and Project ECHO partners' electronic protected health information (e-PHI) in highly-available cloud-based systems with provable certifications, audits and compliance in HITRUST, HITECH, HIPAA, SSAE-16, etc. -Contribute to writing strategic grants, participate in Kaggle.com competitions, perform technology consulting and help develop ECHO's innovative intellectual property portfolio. -Serve on the Board of Directors of the New Mexico Telehealth Alliance -Represent Project ECHO as member of American Telemedicine Association (e.g. ATA)

title: Product Design, Data Science, Information Technology and Engineering Consultant (Part Time)
description: Registered Professional Engineer. Provide part time design consultation on numerous short duration projects. Sampling of projects include: -2014: Stealth, very-early-stage start up. Contributed as Data Scientist to establish Big Data infrastructure, data flows, statistical analyses, predictive modeling and outcomes reporting primarily utilizing the R programming language. -2013: Silicon Valley stealth start up. Provided consulting in systems engineering analysis and product design conceptual architectures. -2007: Private Investor (Albuquerque, New Mexico). Provided parametric modeling, data feed integration and proof-of-concept back- and forward-testing utilizing Neuroshell Trader Professional(tm) to validate and improve private investor's proposed ETF-based trading system. -2006: Sandia National Laboratories (Albuquerque, New Mexico): Provided automation design consulting on the conceptual design of a high energy physics power plant. Conceived and presented at international conference at Sandia National Laboratories automation design which included introducing second robotic arm, which resulted in 4x throughput improvement. -1996: Maytag Appliances (Newton, Iowa): Provided product design consulting on optimizing structural integrity (shock/vibration) of Neptune washer and dryer, integrating novel dispenser into Venus "stack" unit, developing many novel future appliance concepts while in Maytag Labs including top-loading dryer and no-agitator washer. Was awarded utility patent for dispenser for Venus "stack" unit. -1983: Endotherapeutics (Redwood City, CA): Provided product design consulting on suite of disposable safety trocars. (Endotherapeutics was later acquired by US Surgical)

title: Director of IT, Project ECHO
description: o Nominated/approved to Board of Directors of New Mexico Telehealth Alliance in January, 2014 representing Project ECHO. o Direct ECHO IT team consisting of 15 FTE's and 5 students performing: -software development (LAMP and WISC stacks) of clinic mgmt and disease mgmt educational applications. -operational support of ~30 teleECHO clinics per week using mixture of Zoom.US and Polycom for VTC and LoopUp for audio bridging -engineered next-generation teleECHO Clinic video conferencing H/W and S/W architecture, including leading team that evaluated ~20 potential web and video conferencing vendors, built consensus and ultimately chose Zoom. -program support, including Western States Consortium for Hepatitus C, CMMI for Complex Care, Army/DoD replication for Chronic Pain, and many others -ECHO replication support, including across the US, Northern Ireland, India, Canada, Brazil, Uraguay, Ghana, Viet Nam, and other countries. -strategic and operational IT support of all ECHO mobile devices, workstations, servers and website (echo.unm.edu) -grant application support for general ECHO proposal efforts and lead on ECHO IT-specific proposal efforts. -represent Project ECHO as member of American Telemedicine Association (e.g. ATA)

title: Manager, Learning Environments
description: -Explore and prototype advanced IT technologies within learning environment "space" with goal to enhance student success. Areas of exploration include: high definition video cameras, remote live broadcasting, rapid encoders/decoders, web & video conferencing, digital signage and kiosks, IPTV, large displays, interactive white boards, et al. -Contributed content to UNM's Learning Environments Design Guideline. -Managing projects to stand up new IT services including Meeting.UNM (based on Adobe Connect) and UNM on iTunes U. -Part-time, temporary instructor with Mechanical Engineering. Since 2009, have taught five sections of Mechanical Engineering Design 1 (ME160) and one section of Engineering Thermodynamics (ME 301).

title: Special Assistant to the VPR for Advanced Technology
description: Half-time assignment since May, 2009 to support VPR and OVPR with current state technology assessment, gap analysis, advanced technology implementation and other tasks as assigned: 1) Proposal Development (PD) roll-out: Helped assess current state of PD pilot program, recommended a PD RFP process, co-authored PD RFP, chaired PD bid evaluation committee which recommended Cayuse 424 as appropriate hosted solution, helped negotiate T's & C's w/ AVP & Cayuse and was project manager (and one of three system administrators) for Cayuse 424 training and roll-out across UNM in March, 2010. 2) Proposal and Award Tracking: Helped negotiate T's & C's w/ AVP and Cayuse for Cayuse SP. Contributed as team member of project to stand-up Cayuse SP....Cayuse SP now live. 3) Physical Server Virtualization: Led team in establishment of framework to migrate physical Proposal Tracking application servers and OVPR Web servers to virtualized environment within UNM IT Data Center. 4) Conferences Attended for OVPR: Federal Demonstration Partnership, InfoEd User Conference, Cayuse User Conference 5) Steering Committees: Member of InfoEd Client Advisory Group until Mar, 2010 and Cayuse 424 Steering Committees until June, 2011.
